<SECOND>PM-APME Convention,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>APME President Urges Editors: Fight Campaign Attempts To Manage
News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers must fight attempts by presidential campaigns to orchestrate the news in hopes of getting good television coverage, says the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors association. `` The most important journalism in this campaign is being delivered by the reporters who are going in after the candidates have been there and are talking to voters about impressions of the candidates and about the real problems of their regions,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giles </PERSON>, vice president and executive editor of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> APME </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, the first day of its annual convention. He told the newspaper editors: ` My premise is that newspaper editors are allowing television news directors and the campaign strategists for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to influence their Page 1 agendas.'' `` As a result,'' he added, `` we are the targets of criticism about biased or frivolous coverage that is more appropriately the fault of television.'' <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> suggested newspapers rely on wire services for much of the day-to-day campaign coverage, and concentrate on providing readers with `` issues stories.'' On the wide perception that the current campaign has been especially negative, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> vice president and executive editor, said contests in the 1960s, such as the Goldwater-Johnson race in 1964, were no less strident or less shaped by image-makers. `` We, meaning the people who report the campaign, have been telling the voters this is a campaign of sound bites, crafted by handlers and interpreted by spin-control specialists,'' he said. `` Those buzzwords make it sound as though these were all 1988 creations. I do n't think there's anything unique about it.'' More than 600 editors from around the country are attending the week-long annual convention. The AP, the largest newsgathering organization in the world, serves 1,467 daily newspapers. In his address to the editors, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President and General Manager <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said the wire service is in the midst of its most extensive modernization in its photography, financial and technical delivery services. `` As our periodic announcements may have suggested to you, we are in the midst of the most thorough and concentrated rebuilding and modernizing of AP services that has been attempted in modern times,'' <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said. Editors also heard presentations from <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> editors on developments in news and photography distribution, and discussions of changes in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its press. <PERSON> Stanislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Menshikov </PERSON>, a Soviet economist who collaborated with <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> on a book about the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, told the editors that economic change is meeting some resistance from the Soviet bureaucracy. `` They still control most of the economy and make economic change a fiction and not a fact,'' <PERSON> Menshikov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fears of communism and Soviet fears of capitalism have abated in recent years. `` We live in a time when both of those fears have evaporated, except on the paranoiac right,'' he said. At a session on the Soviet press, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalnev </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, said Soviet newspapers reacted to greater press freedom with more negative stories about their country and more positive ones on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He cited an `` upsurge in the inclination to write as many negative things as we could find out'' and said the boundaries on what is acceptable still are being defined. At a panel discussion on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyhan </PERSON>, political columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>, advised the visiting editors to `` watch where you walk and how you drive.'' `` Driving is the most dangerous thing you can do in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, even more than taking advice from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Judson </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> magazine, said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s greatest export is its conscience `` The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> conscience never kept anyone from doing anything, but it does keep you from enjoying it,'' he said.
