<HEAD>Robber Takes Bank Manager Hostage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with manager freed. Picks up
4th graf pvs, `A nearby...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>READING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gunman robbed a bank Tuesday, kidnapped the bank manager and drove off in the manager's car, only to be cornered by a police roadblock on an interstate, authorities said. The manager, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, 61, was freed about seven hours after police closed Interstate 176, a spur from Interstate 76 leading to Reading, said <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, a police communications operator. Negotiations with the gunmman continued late Tuesday, Mrs. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. A state police SWAT team and an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> tactical team arrived at the scene six hours after the standoff began about 10 miles south of this southeast <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> city, said a <LOCATION> Berks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> dispatch supervisor who declined to give her name. A nearby access road was closed because traffic seemed to startle the gunman, the supervisor said. The suspect's brother was brought to the scene in an effort to persuade him to surrender, but the robber asked his brother to leave, said the supervisor. Police asked the suspect to exchange the bank manager for an officer, but he turned the offer down, authorities said. The man was armed with a 9mm pistol, said <ORGANIZATION> Amity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Township </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Eschbach </PERSON>, who questioned several witnesses to the robbery. The robber, identified by police only as a 29-year-old from the <LOCATION> Pottstown </LOCATION> area, took the manager hostage at 4 p.m. at the <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amity </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION>, according to an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent who spoke on condition of anonymity. Police believe less than $ 5,000 was taken, said the <LOCATION> Berks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> supervisor.
