<FIRST>r w PM-PurgatoryAmendments     10-18 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Purgatory Amendments,720</SECOND>
<BYLINE>WASHINGTON TODAY: ``Sorry, Senator. Your Amendment Was Sent to
Purgatory.''
^By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is the amendment in purgatory? Only the category will tell. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, struggling to deal with hundreds of amendments to a bill providing new ammunition for the war on drugs, hammered together a system designed to speed its work and permit <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to adjourn for the year. At times it appeared that the labor-and-time-saving device might prove a tottering house of cards that would bring all progress to a halt. It worked this way: The amendments were assigned to categories. With some, the skids were greased. With others, the road ahead was rocky indeed. Still others faced a fate uncertain. Category 1 amendments were offered as a package containing scores of legislative initiatives and eventually all were approved on a single bloc vote. Category 2 amendments might stand a chance, but only if they were approved by a panel of senators from both parties. Decisions could be appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic leaders. `` Those are the purgatory amendments,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` They do not know where they are going. And they may not be going anywhere.'' Category 3 amendments could be offered individually and face their chances. Category 4 amendments did not make the cut and had no chance at all. It took unanimous consent of all 100 senators for the gears to mesh and the system to move forward. The spur to getting that consent was the desire of many senators facing re-election contests to leave the capital and get on with campaigning. Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, had a complaint. `` I had an amendment and I find it is not even on the purgatory list,'' he said. `` That raises the question to me whether my amendment went to heaven or hell,'' he said. `` How do I find that out?'' `` It went to hell,'' replied Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>: `` I know the senator from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> might want me to go there, but where did my amendment go? <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>: `` It is on list No. 4. `` What happens to list No. 4? <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> asked. `` Nothing,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> replied.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Bean soup, that enduring congressional culinary tradition, has been on the menu of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Restaurant for most of the days of this century, every day for the last 85 years at least. But being on the menu does not necessarily mean being on the stove or on the table. And one day 45 years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> recalled, the bean soup pots stopped bubbling for the first time ever. `` Even though bean soup was on the menu that day at 10 cents a cup, 15 cents a bowl, it was n't cooking on the stove,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. The day was Sept. 14, 1943, and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was beanless and therefore soupless. `` This was because war-time rationing had slashed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s supply of white <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> beans,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> explained `` Somehow, by the next day, more beans were found and bowls of bean soup have been ladled up without any interruption ever since,'' he said. Bean soup is on the menu in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> because it was ordered to be there. There is some question as to who gave the orders. Some attribute the decree to Sen. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> DuBois </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Bean soup was his favorite and he presided over the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> which in turn presided over the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> restaurant. Therefore, bean soup went on the menu. Others say the demand was made in 1903 by Sen. <PERSON> Knute </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. The rage for bean soup soon spread to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and in 1904 Speaker <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION>, was outraged that the menu of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> restaurant did not list it. For years Cannon's words on the subject were also printed on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> menu, along with a recipe for the now famous soup: `` Thunderation, I had my mouth set for bean soup. From now on, hot or cold, rain, snow or shine, I want it on the menu every day.'' There are many differences in the operating styles of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said that the preparation of bean soup is one of them. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> recipe calls for adding onions braised in butter. The House recipe calls for beans, beans, beans _ nothing but beans.
</TEXT>
