<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-18 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dairy Farmers To Benefit From New Government Computer System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers soon will be getting information from a new computer system devised by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to help them select only the best cows for their milking herds _ the cream of the crop, so to speak. The genetic evaluation system, called the Animal Model, takes into account more of a cow's relatives than does the older system, the Modified Contemporary Comparison, which has been used since 1974, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Under the new system, milk production of a cow's daughters will be considered when the mother is being evaluated. And the evaluation of bulls, based in part on the records of the male's offspring, also take into account the impact of the bull's mate on those offspring The new system will be used for the first time in dairy genetic evaluations to be prepared in July 1989, the report said. The information then will be reported to dairy farmers who can use it to decide which cows and their calves to keep in the herd. `` With this information in hand, the farmer can select with more accuracy the calves likely to be the most efficient milk producers,'' the report said. The new system, a revision of the older method, was developed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiggans </PERSON>, a research geneticist at the agency's facility in <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>, Md. The older method was developed by <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>. Agency work in genetic evaluation for many years has been an important part of a nationwide effort to improve the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dairy herd. Milk output rose from 7,029 pounds per cow in 1960 to 13,293 pounds in 1986, the report said. The trend has continued, with <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> figures showing the average milk production last year rose further to an average of 13,932 pounds. `` Approximately 60,000 farmers participate in the improvement program, which involves recording milk production of each cow for one day every month,'' the report said. `` Information on each animal is compiled and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Improvement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>, home to approximately 39 million milk production records on 15 million cows.'' The participating dairy farmers then receive reports on each of their animals, the report said. <PERSON> Wiggans </PERSON> began working on the new system two years ago and in May 1987 transferred the programs to computers at the <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supercomputer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facility </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>, N.Y. The <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> supercomputer has a very large memory, which was necessary to handle all the additional details of the evaluations, including all the relatives of milk cows, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The financial worth of burley tobacco producers is far below the national average for other farmers, but they also have fewer debts, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> study says. The study by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> involved 273 burley tobacco farms surveyed by questionnaire in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> for the 1984 crop, the most recent information available. It said the net worth of burley tobacco producers averaged $ 130,715, substantially below the $ 322,732 average for all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm producers. The average farm debt for burley farms was about a third less than the average for all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm producers. According to the report, which was distributed here on Monday, the farms produced an average of 2.3 acres of burley, a cigarette tobacco. The crop is labor intensive and required an average of 240 hours of family and hired labor per acre, or 13 hours per 100 pounds of leaf produced in 1984. An additional 11 hours of custom labor was used on each acre. The 2.3 acres of burley tobacco was grown on farms averaging a total of 122 acres of farmland. `` Most farms relied on non-farm sources to supplement their income,'' the report said. `` Small tobacco farms with less than 2.1 acres of burley generally averaged equal sales from crops and livestock. Large tobacco farms with 6 or more acres of burley tobacco depended less on livestock sales, receiving more than 70 percent of their gross cash farm income from crop sales.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new labeling law in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> may restrict that country's imports of soybean oil in favor of other kinds of vegetable oil, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> trade report. The law requires that some labels for edible vegetable oil containers indicated `` oil for dressing and frying,'' while other labels indicate `` oil for dressing'' only, says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Basis for the labeling is whether the vegetable oil contains 2 percent or less of linolenic acid, which would qualify as `` oil for dressing and frying.'' If the acid content is more than that, it would be restricted to dressings. Sunflowerseed oil, which is produced widely in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, has the lower acid content and would qualify as a dual-purpose oil. <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. However, soybean oil, mostly from outside the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> _ including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ has 7 percent linolenic acid and would be restricted to dressings, the report said.
</TEXT>
