<HEAD>US Aid to Egypt, Pakistan Criticized as Hurting Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to Egyptian and Pakistani government agencies undercuts the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policy of helping private business and discouraging government-owned enterprise, congressional investigators have concluded. A report by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors government spending for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, cited as an example the fact that the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> had encouraged <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to end agricultural subsidies but also had financed $ 142 million in fertilizer and $ 123 million in wheat and cotton imports that the Pakistani government sells to farmers and consumers at subsidized prices. The largest of these `` commodity import programs'' benefit <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has had $ 3 billion worth of this kind of aid since 1975, the report said. Official AID policy holds that goods received by government-owned enterprises at subsidized prices hurt a country's development because they discourage sales at market prices The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also reported that the Egyptian government had piled up $ 325 million worth of Egyptian pounds _ representing more than half the proceeds from sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid goods _ instead of using the money for development projects. `` ... The cost of this large accumulation of local currencies remaining idle is high in terms of missed opportunities to support development,'' the report said. The report included a memo from <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bissell </PERSON>, the assistant AID administrator, saying that the Egyptian government has tentatively promised to release about $ 165 million worth of the local currency for development efforts this year and next. The congressional investigators said that when asked about the situation, AID officials in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> `` acknowledged the detrimental effects of subsidies, but said the political dimension of these programs limited their leverage in moving these programs to achieve greater impact.''
