<HEAD>Rates on Short-Term T-Bills Highest in Nearly Three Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities rose in the latest auction to the highest level in more than three years. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.1 billion in three-month bills Monday at an average discount rate of 7.36 percent, up from 7.32 percent last week. Another $ 7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.55 percent, up from 7.46 percent last week. The rates were the highest since May 13, 1985, when three-month bills sold for 7.69 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.90 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 7.60 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,814.00 and and 7.96 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,618.30. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 8.07 percent last week after averaging 8.13 percent the week before.
