 A dozen black operators of <ORGANIZATION> Burger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> restaurants have charged in a lawsuit that the fast-food company gave black franchise holders uprofitable locations and reserved more lucrative outlets for white operators. The discrimination and anti-trust lawsuit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday, charged that <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> also gave white operators more favorable financing terms. Blacks were charged as much as twice what white operators paid to purchase or lease stores and equipment, the lawsuit said. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, a Burger King spokeswoman, said Monday, `` We ca n't really respond until we have had an opportunity to see the suit and evaluate what the allegations are. The Miami-based company also was accused of discouraging black franchise holders from expanding to other locations by thwarting their attempts to obtain loans. The black operators also charged that the company did not give them the opportunity to obtain franchises for lucrative downtown locations, which subsequently were awarded to whites. Blacks who were awarded franchises in middle - and upper-income neighborhoods were leased stores that had `` deficient equipment, poor dining facilities, poor parking and drive-thru locations and inferior sales potential,'' the suit said The lawsuit, which seeks $ 500 million in punitive and compensatory damages, also accused company officials of trying to `` harass, threaten, coerce, intimidate and otherwise malign'' franchise holders after learning of their plans to file the suit. The lawsuit also charged that Burger King intentionally misrepresented the sales potential of locations sold to black operators. In addition to the 12 named plaintiffs, the lawsuit was brought 