' <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, campaign manager for <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>, said in a telephone interview. `` We want to bring more and better jobs to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>.'' `` If you look all over our advertising, it's pretty monotone,'' he said. <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>'s strategy to win black support is direct: `` We're asking,'' said <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> `` That sounds pretty simple, but we are.'' `` We're not giving up any vote to <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowdy </PERSON>,'' he said. `` He's spending a lot of money,'' said <PERSON> Dowdy </PERSON> campaign spokesman <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Pittman </PERSON>. `` But basically what he's spending money on is disguising his abysmal record on civil rights.'' While polls show <PERSON> Lott </PERSON> leading overall in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race, they also indicate he has barely dented black support for Dowdy. An independent poll conducted in late September and early October by <ORGANIZATION> Mason-Dixon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> showed <PERSON> Lott </PERSON> leading Dowdy 49 percent to 41 percent with 10 percent undecided. Among black voters, though, the poll shows Dowdy with a 10-to-1 lead over <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>. The poll, which surveyed 812 likely voters, has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points. Although there are two major-party black candidates running for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this year, <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, both are Republicans and are considered long shots in races against popular Democrats, former Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. Both Republicans and Democrats say the two black <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates are not tokens nominated to water down traditional support for the Democrats. `` <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> ... was in no sense hand-picked,'' said <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senatorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` In <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON>' case, he has fought any attempt to make it look like he is a token black running.''
