<HEAD>Ex President Galtieri Defends 1982 Decision To Invade Falklands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE F. LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President Gen. <PERSON> Leopoldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON>, on trial for mismanaging the 1982 war with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> over the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, says he would invade the territory again and does not regret starting a war. `` ` Would I do it again? Given the same circumstances and conditions, would I proceed in the same manner? The answer is yes. I, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON>, would proceed the same way as I did,'' <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON> said in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. `` What was done, was done well.'' <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON> and two other members of the former ruling junta _ Adm. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Anaya </PERSON> and Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Basilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lami </PERSON> <PERSON> Dozo </PERSON> _ were convicted in May 1986 by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> of military mismanagement. All were sentenced to prison. On July 26, their appeal began in civilian court, along with three officers who had been acquitted by the military's highest tribunal: Vice Adm. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Lombardo </PERSON>, Gen. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Menendez </PERSON>, and Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Parada </PERSON>. The issue is how the war was handled, including <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON>'s decision to send about 12,000 troops to the islands, located 250 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Tierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuego </LOCATION> off the southernmost tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON> questioned the military's tactics and strategy, including <PERSON> Anaya </PERSON>'s decision, as head of the navy, to virtually withdraw the fleet from combat after the cruiser General Belgrano was sunk in early May by a British nuclear submarine. Argentine conscripts were ill-trained, inadequately supplied and poorly led, witnesses said. The conflict began on April 2, 1982, and lasted 74 days. About 700 Argentines were killed along with 255 British troops. In his defense, <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON> said the war for the islands that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> calls the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION> was narrowly lost, so charges of mismanagement are ill-founded. `` The battle for the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, militarily, was lost by a narrow margin,'' he said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> claimed the islands in 1833. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> claims it inherited the islands from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> upon achieving independence in 1810. The underpopulated, windswept islands are home to about 1,900 people, mostly sheep ranchers and fishermen. Also at stake are the rights to potentially large deposits of oil and other natural resources. For <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, nationalism is a factor. Every map calls the islands the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION>. Every school child learns they were seized from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and should be returned. <PERSON> Galtieri </PERSON>, who was sentenced to 12 years in prison by the military tribunal and who faces a stiffer, 20-year sentence if he loses his appeal, was not repentant when he addressed the civilian court. `` In 1982, destiny knocked at the doors of the nation,'' he said. `` And the people, with dignity, decided to fulfill a historical obligation'' and reclaim the islands. The court's decision was expected by early next week.
