<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSCampaign     10-18 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Campaign,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>New AIDS TV Spots Avoid The `C' Word</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top federal official says Americans should look to television networks and other news outlets if they think the government should be more forthright in calling for use of condoms to combat the spread of AIDS. A new wave of television spots unveiled Monday does not mention what one reporter called `` the C word'' but leaves little to the imagination of any viewer who has heard that condoms can help prevent spread of the deadly disease. The 1987 series of television ads distributed to national networks and thousands of individual stations contained direct references to condoms in some spots that got little airplay despite $ 18 million worth of free airtime devoted to less controversial messages. Nonetheless, one of the 1988 ads features a tantalizing episode in which a young man talks to the camera as he puts a sock on his foot. `` If I told you I could save my life just by putting on my socks, you would n't take me seriously,'' says the man, sitting in a chair. `` Because life is never that simple,'' he adds. `` But watch ...'' There are a few seconds of silence as he slips a sock onto his foot. `` Okay, you're right,'' the man says. `` That would n't really save my life. But there's something just as simple that could.'' Questioned at a news conference, Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, said there was a simple answer to why the government avoided specifically mentioning condoms in the new round of television spots. `` We had a great deal of difficulty getting the television stations to use that,'' he said, referring to 1987 spots that specifically mentioned condoms. `` That one was selectively avoided by the television stations.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said designers of the 1987 ad campaign tried to be careful to produce spots that would not be offensive to audiences even though some of them did discuss condoms. But he said experience showed `` there was another level of screening'' at networks and local TV stations that resulted in the condom spots rarely being seen by a general audience. With more than a dozen cameras rolling, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> was among several officials who declined to answer directly when asked whether television executives were engaging in irresponsible behavior in public health by declining to run condom spots. Eventually, <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee-Miller </PERSON>, the administration's top public relations official in the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> who had been moderating the news conference, stepped forward. `` I'll answer it,'' she said. `` No, they're not engaging in responsible behavior.'' She asked reporters to `` challenge the networks'' rather than the health department. Indeed, the print ads and posters prepared for the new campaign deals with condom use in a direct way likely to draw criticism from conservatives. `` If He Wo n't Wear A Condom, Call For Help,'' says one suggested newspaper ad. One of numerous posters features a still photo from the TV spot where the man is putting a sock on his foot. `` Putting On A Condom Is Just As Simple,'' says the headline. Another series of six posters feature photos of three different men and three different women with the same headline on each: ` What Have You Got Against A Condom?'' The smaller print says, `` The simple act of putting on a condom can save your life, if they're used properly and every time you have sex For more information about AIDS and condoms, call 1-800-342-AIDS.'' Another series features three different women all saying, `` If he does n't have a condom, you just have to take a deep breath and tell him to go get one.'' Many critics have said federal officials and <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mather </ORGANIZATION>, the private advertising company hired to produce the campaign, went too far last year in trying to get sexually active Americans to use condoms. Others said the ads were not explicit enough. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said federal health officials have always said that abstinence or a monogamous relationship with an uninfected partner are the only two absolute ways to prevent sexual spread of AIDS. `` Condoms are third best,'' he said, adding it is nonetheless important for health officials to recommend their use for those who are not abstinent or in monogamous relationships with partners they are certain are uninfected.
</TEXT>
