<HEAD>Four States Decide Whether To Gamble On Lotteries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in four states will decide whether to take a chance on a lottery in ballot measures opposed by religious leaders and others who say state-sanctioned gambling exploits the poor. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> have lottery questions on Nov. 8's ballot. The <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> proposition also would clear the way for parimutuel and casino gambling, if the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> approves. Polls in the states indicate support for the issues. Proponents, who include Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and state Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Borst </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, say voting `` yes'' would bring millions of dollars into state coffers, including much-needed money for education and rural economic development. Twenty-eight states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> operate lotteries, which have grossed $ 14.8 billion in fiscal 1988, up 19.2 percent from 1987, according to Gambling and <ORGANIZATION> Wagering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Of that sum, $ 5.6 billion went to state governments and the balance to cover prizes and the cost of administration, according to lottery officials. Opponents argue lotteries encourage betting by the people who can least afford it. `` There are only 3.5 million people in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fugitte </PERSON> of Elizabethtown, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lottery </ORGANIZATION>. `` A million of them are under 18 and 1 million are under the poverty level. ... We ca n't be for something where the more the citizens of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> bet and lose, the better off the state is.'' <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legalized </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gambling </ORGANIZATION> hopes to spend $ 350,000 on advertisements and pamphlets arguing that gambling would attract organized crime to the state. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> held a `` Get Out the Vote Sunday'' to encourage congregations to vote no. Supporters such as <PERSON> Borst </PERSON> counter that such opponents `` are our best salesmen so far as making people aware of it.'' Church leaders in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> including all Lutheran and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops said they will spend the next few weeks urging congregations to vote no. Opposition in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> gained impetus when <PERSON> Morman </PERSON> leaders, usually apolitical in state affairs, began organizing against the lottery. A recent report by the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiscal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> predicts a lottery would produce about $ 134 million in annual net revenues for <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, which has 5.5 million people. Proponents in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> estimate the lottery could mean $ 70 million a year for the state, while supporters in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> say ticket sales would gross $ 40 million to $ 100 million. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, with just 1 million residents, pressure for the lottery has come from the western and northern parts of the state, where promoters say the state is losing millions of dollars to lotteries in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. They project the state could reap at least $ 2 million annually. But the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> institute's president, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, warns that forecasting lottery revenues is about as chancy as winning one, adding that it would be risky for any state to count on specific dollar amounts. `` From a fiscal standpoint, the biggest problem with lottery revenues is their unpredictability,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` This means that it would be unwise to dedicate those revenues to functions that require a stable resource of funding in order to operate.'' The four states stand to lose little if they opt for the game, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikesell </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> professor who has studied lotteries. `` They're basically guaranteed against losing money because we know enough about structuring prizes and operations of lottery,'' he said, adding that none should expect lotteries to be a `` booming success'' like those in more populous, urban states such as <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. The four states voting `` either have substantially rural populations or small populations. Some are smack-dab in between existing lottery states that are doing pretty well or they do n't have a good tradition of gambling history,'' <PERSON> Mikesell </PERSON> said That argument is n't likely to hold water in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, said Fugitte: `` Most of the community either is neutral on the issue of gambling or they think it's all right. You've got to remember this is a horseracing state.''
