<HEAD>Mexican Economic Program Extended into New Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Labor and business leaders hailed President-elect <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s extension of an inflation-fighting program for one month after he takes office. Citing progress under the 10-month-old plan and other economic reforms, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> announced in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday they were preparing as much as $ 3.5 billion in short-term `` bridge'' loans for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Under the Economic Solidarity Pact, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s business, farm and labor sectors and the government pledged last December to cooperate in holding down wages and prices. The latest extension to Dec. 31, published in newspapers on Monday, said recent measures taken by the government were helping hold down inflation. It mentioned a new cut in government spending, continued efforts to close or sell unprofitable and non-strategic state companies, and maintenance of monetary and credit policies that support price stability. `` We will not continue from crisis to crisis, but are going to achieve growth without inflation,'' said <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, in remarks quoted by the Excelsior news service. <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivares </PERSON> <PERSON> Ventura </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campesinos </ORGANIZATION>, said the pact was not `` a straitjacket'' on workers' salaries but rather ensured that wages could be upwardly adjusted under the plan's freeze on official prices. Under the reform pact, labor has foregone wage increases since March, arguing that a small rise would give business a pretext for price hikes _ thus causing workers to lose ground. Prices of basic goods are controlled, but subsidies on many products have been gradually lifted to reduce the budget deficit. The monthly increase in consumer prices has been slashed from 15.5 percent in January to 0.6 percent in September under the plan. The rate for the first nine months of the year was 45.5 percent. When the accord was signed last December, inflation was rising to a rate of 159.2 percent for the year. `` The recent trend in prices has been satisfactory since it allowed the monthly rate of increase in September to reach the lowest level in 12 years,'' the statement said.
