 A private study indicates as many as 5 million children are going to bed hungry in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> made what it called the conservative estimate after a house-to-house survey of nearly 800 low-income families in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and said it would extend the study to seven other states over the next 15 months. But on the basis of the early data from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state `` ... we estimate conservatively that 2 million to 5 million children in this country could now have a serious hunger problem,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fersh </PERSON>, executive director of the center, said Monday. Similar studies are now under way in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
