<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-BasesOutlook     10-18 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Bases Outlook,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Faces Sell Job, Disappointment Due To Excess
Expectations</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> faces a hard road in selling the newly concluded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases agreement to the public and may be forced to harden her position on the thornier issue of the installations' status after 1991. First reaction to the agreement, signed Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, was at best mixed. Major newspapers accused the government of selling out by agreeing to allow the six bases to remain through 1991 in return for `` only'' $ 962 million in American aid. That was more than 2 -LCB- times the $ 180 million a year which President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> pledged in 1983 over a five-year period to now-ousted President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. But the fact that the <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION> won far more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance was all but lost on the public and press due to the government's having raised expectations which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats all along said were unrealistic Even before the talks began April 5, <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> newspapers quoted unidentified government sources as saying the Aquino administration would insist on $ 1.2 billion a year. Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> never explicitly confirmed the $ 1.2 billion demand but termed it `` reasonable.'' <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> aides privately told Filipino reporters that the government would hold fast to its demands. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> himself said repeatedly that compensation was not the only issue. But other issues he cited, such as confirmation of nuclear weapons at the bases and expanded criminal jurisdiction over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, were not addressed in the new agreement. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> told reporters he was optimistic that once the Filipino public understood the agreement, `` they will accept it.'' Indeed, one longtime bases opponent, Sen. <PERSON> Aquilino </PERSON> <PERSON> Pimentel </PERSON>, said the results of the negotiations `` are certainly much better than before.'' But the absence of a detailed explanation by the government of the benefits of the agreement opened the door to criticism from the press and some lawmakers, who hope to make the bases an issue in the runup to the 1992 national elections. Under the new Constitution, any extension after 1991 must be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where opposition to the bases is strong. Several senators are widely assumed to harbor presidential ambitions and are casting for an issue in the 1992 election, in which Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> says she will not be a candidate. The fact that the latest agreement was hammered out in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and not <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, raised charges that the government had indulged in the same kind of secret diplomacy for which the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> administration had been roundly criticized. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> has been in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for nearly a month. When asked whether Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> herself was fully aware of all aspects of the final negotiations, her spokesman <PERSON> Teodoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> replied `` I do n't think so.'' Instead, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> left details of the negotiations to <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, who has not entirely shaken off his longtime image as an `` Am-Boy,'' or `` American Boy,'' a derogatory term for Filipinos who support <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests. That strategy appeared designed in part to allow Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to escape personal political damage if the public found the agreement unsatisfactory. The results of the just concluded talks were expected to influence the government's decision on whether to negotiate a new pact extending the bases beyond 1991. Such negotiations _ assuming they are held _ will be difficult. Recent surveys show a majority of Filipinos favor retention of the bases but under favorable terms, including fixed rent. But Communist rebels and a significant portion of the urban middle class, including journalists and intellectuals, are strongly opposed to the bases, regardless of the financial impact if they were closed. `` We seem to have hung out a price tag on our sovereignty and national dignity,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Letty </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez-Magsanoc </PERSON> in the Philippine Daily Inquirer. `` We are now selling out even when the price is n't right.'' In such a climate, issues which are viewed here as basic to national sovereignty are likely to be raised. These include formal notification of the presence of nuclear weapons as well as military operations launched from <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> soil. Filipino military officers are routinely barred from some sensitive areas such as code rooms, even though the six bases are nominally under Philippine command.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ EDITOR'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> has been a foreign correspondent for 11 years and has been chief of the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> bureau of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1986.
