<SECOND>PM-Mafia Informer,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Drops Drug Charges Against Mob Informant Tommaso Buscetta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heroin smuggling charges have been dismissed against a key Mafia informant who testified against his associates at the `` maxi-trial'' in <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION> and the `` pizza connection'' drug case here. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government officially dropped the six-count indictment Monday, saying <PERSON> Tommaso </PERSON> <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> had `` fulfilled the terms'' of his cooperation agreement with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Italian governments. `` <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> has provided, and continues to provide, exhaustive information concerning the activities of the Mafia here and in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> in court papers. `` Moreover, largely as a result of <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON>'s testimony at trials in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, hundreds of defendants have been convicted of heroin trafficking and associated organized crime activity.'' The drug indictment against <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> was filed in 1973 in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. The order to dismiss the indictment, which contained the only outstanding charges against <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON>, was signed by Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>. Its dismissal was included in a cooperation agreement <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> entered with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Italian governments in 1985. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> had been a soldier `` of great respect'' in the Sicilian Mafia, where his duties included settling disputes and acting as an emissary between families. His testimony at the `` pizza connection'' trial helped convict 18 defendants of participating in a Mafia-backed drug racket, operated in part through pizza parlors, that imported an estimated $ 1.6 billion worth of heroin into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He was the prosecution's first witness at the 17-month trial that ended in March 1986, and he identified certain defendants as members of the Sicilian Mafia. <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> also was among a dozen admitted Mafia members who testified at the Italian trial, described as the largest Mafia trial ever conducted. More than 300 defendants were convicted in that case last year. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> would remain in a witness protection program administered by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. He has been given a new identity and is living in this country.
