<FIRST>r i PM-EnglishingScotland     10-18 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Englishing Scotland,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0404 to fix category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scots Agonize Over `Englishing Of Scotland'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has suffered another blow to its sense of separate identity: The English have overrun its cultural establishment. Ever since 1707, when <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> were united under one crown and parliament, Scots have worried about being swamped by their English neighbors, who outnumber them 11-1. Comes now `` The Englishing of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' broadcast Aug. 29 on the independent Scottish television channel, which shows the command posts of Scottish culture firmly in the hands of Sassenachs from south of the border. Not the artists, mind. Native Scottish creativity has never looked healthier. What worries guardians of Scottish identity is the preponderance of Englishmen in a cultural bureaucracy supposed to be separate. `` The Englishing of Scottish life is a process that has gone on for many years, but many Scots ... feel it is beginning to undermine the very notion of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON>, the writer and host, said in introducing the program. <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> presented impressive of evidence of `` non-Scot'' infiltration, the non-Scots being almost invariably from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Non-Scots run most of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s major state-subsidized arts institutions: the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museums </ORGANIZATION>, National Galleries, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, Scottish Opera, Scottish Ballet, its three major international arts festivals and the Scottish National Trust for heritage parks and buildings. They run five of the eight universities, 10 of the 15 government-funded colleges and three of the six leading theaters. `` We are assimilating ourselves toward an English ideal and gradually I think we will assimilate ourselves out of existence,'' <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, a playwright, historian and Scottish nationalist, said on the program. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, a retired diplomat, said: `` I think we're at very grave risk of ceasing to exist as a recognizable nation, as a recognizable culture and identity. The species is under threat.'' While everyone saw a problem, there was little agreement on the cause. Newspaper columnist <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Ascherson </PERSON> said most of the institutions mentioned were recent creations copied from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` The idea of cultural bureaucracies is entirely alien to <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` This is not a country which has traditionally been kind to the arts.'' Some said Scots were reluctant to protest `` Englishing'' for fear of sounding racist. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, editor of the left-wing journal `` Radical <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' said this fear had deprived Scots of `` the confidence to stand up and argue that there is a problem.'' <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Massie </PERSON>, a conservative writer, offered simple arithmetic: `` Because of the population ratio, if you have a job that is publicly advertised and you have 10 applicants, you're quite likely to find that seven of them come from outside <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, an Englishman who heads the National Gallery of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, called the program `` absolute arrant nonsense.'' He said just as many Scots run English institutions, but <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> reported no Scots among 34 university heads in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, and said only two of the 21 state-funded museums, art galleries and libraries south of the border were run by <ORGANIZATION> Scots </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> argued that `` An Englishman sometimes understands more and can better identify the Scottishness of something than a Scot can.'' The program, too, paid tribute to the many non-Scots who have fostered Scottish art forms the Scots themselves had neglected. Overall, however, <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON>'s presentation painted a gloomy portrait of a culture hijacked by outsiders. It inspired a deluge of commentary and letters that complained of `` Englishing'' in everything from soccer through architecture to the Englishisms creeping into everyday speech in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The Advisory Council for the Arts in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> weighed in with worry about `` the survival of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> as anything more than a geographical expression.'' <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> said the letters ran 8-2 in support of his conclusions, which are that `` certain jobs should be reserved for people who are educated and brought up in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and understand the nuances of Scottish culture.'' He acknowledges the impossibility of barring Englishmen from jobs in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> since both are part of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, but added in an interview: `` It's similarly daft that so many such jobs are being taken by non-Scots. That's the ambivalence of our whole constitutional situation.'' The broadcast coincides with a broadly based campaign for limited independence that is gathering support in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` There does seem to be a fairly stronger feeling of nationalism again,'' <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> said. `` I think Scots have a pendulum consciousness that swings from feeling British to feeling Scottish, and in my opinion it's swinging toward Scottishness now.''
</TEXT>
