<HEAD>Hirohito Receives Emergency Transfusion, But Reported Stable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with condition stable after emergency transfusions.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> lost a large amount of blood early today but was in stable condition after being given emergency blood transfusions, palace officials said. Doctors gave the frail 87-year-old monarch a total of 1.3 pints of blood overnight to compensate for the bleeding, the officials said. It was the largest amount of blood the emperor has lost since he discharged close to 2.1 pints from his bowels on Oct. 1, news reports said. <PERSON> Iwao </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyao </PERSON>, vice grand steward of the <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said there had been no new discharge as of this afternoon, but doctors were ready to administer more blood at any time. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has been in serious condition since Sept. 19 when his internal bleeding, thought to be coming from his upper intestine, caused him to vomit a large amount of blood. Doctors believe the discharge this morning came from blood that had accumulated over time from his internal hemorrhaging, palace officials said. Palace spokesman <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> told reporters the world's oldest living monarch was `` in stable condition and fully conscious.'' He said <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> had eaten small amounts of porridge during the past four days, the first food he has had since Oct. 1. Doctors have been concerned about the emperor's declining nutritional status caused by his intraveneous feeding, which is unable to provide enough nutrients. Today's transfusions brought the total amount of blood <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has received since his condition worsened to 19.8 pints, reportedly about twice the total amount of blood in his body. The emperor underwent an intestinal bypass operation a year ago after an enlarged pancreas put pressure on his intestine, blocking the passage of food. Imperial Household officials said then he was suffering from chronic pancreatitis and no signs of pancreatic cancer were found.
