<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Civilians Killed in Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunmen wearing military-style uniforms shot and stabbed six people to death in eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, an army spokesman said today. The official, who can not be identified under briefing rules, said four Tamil and two Sinhalese men were shot and stabbed late Monday in the village of <LOCATION> Seyiliyamadu </LOCATION>, about 175 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, the island's capital. The official said the slayings could have been done by either militant Tamils fighting for a separate nation in the northeastern province or extremist Sinhalese opposed to the government's peace overtures to the Tamil rebels. Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, comprise 18 percent of the island's 16 million people. Militant Tamils have been fighting since 1983 for an independent homeland in the northeast. A peace accord aimed at ending the 5-year-old insurgency offered Tamils limited automony in the region, and election of a provincial council is scheduled for Nov. 19. In exchange, Tamil rebels must surrender their weapons and end the fighting that has claimed at least 8,500 lives. The most militant group, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ealam </ORGANIZATION>, accepted the agreement after it was signed by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> in July 1987. They reneged three months later, saying it did not meet enough demands, and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> sent an estimated 47,000 troops to the island to put down the rebellion. Radicals in the Sinhalese community, which makes up 75 percent of the island's population and controls the government, also oppose the peace accord. They claim it grants too many concessions to the Tamils. They have vowed to kill anyone who supports the agreement and have been blamed for more than 500 deaths in the past year, including members of the governing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
