that explained the decision, it said. Police declined to release the words of the notes or tape, which <PERSON> Slamka </PERSON> said ran no more than a minute. `` This was n't spontaneous,'' <PERSON> Slamka </PERSON> said. `` It was planned, though I'm not sure how long it was pre-planned.'' The bodies were discovered after <PERSON> Bollis </PERSON>' father came to the home and met <PERSON> Kruczkowski </PERSON>'s mother. She went to the attic of the wood-frame house, where her son lived with his father, and found the bodies, <PERSON> Slamka </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kruczkowski </PERSON>'s parents are divorced. The .30 -06 - caliber rifle was owned by the <PERSON> Kruczkowski </PERSON>'s father, who also had other rifles in There was no evidence that the boys had used drugs or alcohol, the chief said. `` In fact, I'm not aware of any problems with the two of them.'' <PERSON> Slamka </PERSON> said he could not recall another case of a multiple suicide in his 25 years on the force. `` From time to time we have gunshot suicides and young people are involved,'' he said. `` Each time it's especially tragic, and in the event of a double suicide, it multiplies the loss and the concern you have for these people.'' Early Monday, <PERSON> Slamka </PERSON> sent his school liaison officer to the high school to meet with the principal. The deaths were announced over the public address system and students were told counselors were available to help them. Similar steps were taken at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Calumet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, about 70 miles north of <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Bollis </PERSON> was a student, officials said. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwaller </PERSON>, a social worker for the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S