<SECOND>PM-Pumpkin Shortage,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customers May Find Fewer Big Jack-O'-Lanterns After Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vana </PERSON> <PERSON> LaCost </PERSON> says her customers can get the great pumpkin _ but they'll have to shop early. Drought has reduced the number of jumbo jack-o'lanterns in her eight-acre patch as in other areas of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` The decorative pumpkin crop is short and people -LRB- in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> -RRB- will be paying more than usual for large pumpkins,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON>, a pumpkin specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. `` The problem area is as wide as the drought.'' Pumpkin growers in the East have a good crop, but shipping them to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> is expensive and adds to the price, <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON> said. Decorative pumpkins are grown on smaller plots, usually near urban areas. And because farmers often can not afford to irrigate, the drought can cause significant damage. This year, seed failed to germinate in the sun-baked Midwestern soil, and vines that did grow either failed to produce as many pumpkins, or produced smaller fruit than in previous years. <PERSON> Gerber </PERSON> said many growers in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> realized their crop would be smaller when the vines started dying and uncovering the fruit. `` It will be the late shopper who has problems. The last week before Halloween could be tight,'' Mrs. <PERSON> LaCost </PERSON>, whose farm is near <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION>, predicted Monday. She said she has kept pace with demand so far and the quality of her pumpkins is good, but the drought cut her volume in half. She would not specify her prices, but said they are a little higher than last year. Consumers wo n't have to worry about a shortage of canned pumpkins for holiday pies, say officials in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, which leads the country with about 5,000 acres of the commercially canned product. `` We had a super year,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohrs </PERSON>, plant manager for the <ORGANIZATION> Libby </ORGANIZATION> division of <ORGANIZATION> Carnation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Libby </PERSON> processes about 100,000 tons of pumpkins a year at its Morton plant <PERSON> Rohrs </PERSON> said the size of the pumpkins was smaller than usual, but the amount of fruit available was excellent. He said <PERSON> Libby </PERSON>'s variety was deep-rooted and survived the summer drought well. However, about 40 percent of <PERSON> Libby </PERSON>'s growers use irrigation. `` Our pumpkins were the best they ever were,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Tazewell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> farmer who raises 180 acres of pumpkins for <LOCATION> Libby </LOCATION> on irrigated land. He said his yields ranged from 33 tons per acre to nearly 41 tons per acre, and <PERSON> Libby </PERSON> paid $ 17 a ton for the crop.
