<SECOND>PM-Official English,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman, Chavez Quit U.S. English Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of a group that wants English to be the nation's official language says he resigned to let voters focus on the issue instead of on allegations about his ties to advocates of forced sterilization. The controversy has `` come to center more around me in the last week or 10 days,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> said Monday. He said his resignation from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English, which he co-founded, would give him time to fight accusations. His decision followed announcements by former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> newsman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON> that they were severing their ties with the organization. Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said Monday she was quitting because she had been told that some major contributors to <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON>'s other interests advocated unusual views on population and immigration control, including advocacy of forced sterilization. `` To me it is just not consistent with the views I hold,'' she said. <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON> resigned from the advisory board to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English on Oct. 6 after learning of a 2-year-old <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> memo. That memo, distributed at a 1986 immigration conference, posed a series of questions and depicted an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> possibly doomed to conflict between a minority of educated well-off English speakers and a majority of uneducated poor people of other ethnic and racial groups with faster population growth. <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> on Monday described the memo as `` a compilation of questions and views of many observers on complex and controversial issues.'' `` Our opponents have falsely charged that it reflects the views of myself or <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English and its positions on these initiatives,'' he added. `` There is no connection between a memo I wrote in 1986 and the initiatives for the ballot in November 1988.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English backs measures in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> next month. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s Proposition 106, if approved, would change the state constitution to designate English as the state's official language and limit government use of foreign languages in courts, meetings and schools. Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said at least one major contributor to U.S. English helped reprint `` an awful, awful book'' called `` Camp of the Saints,'' which she described as `` a paranoid fantasy'' about `` undesirables of the Third World'' taking over developed nations. She said she had been told that <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON>'s activities with immigration and population-control groups involved some who may have given money to `` groups that may be involved in eugenics research.'' She said one person favored forced sterilization but she did not elaborate. <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> said he did not know who the people <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> was talking about. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English gets most of its funds from <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> corporation run by <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON>'s wife and two <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> men. Records show <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> gets most of its funds from direct-mail solicitation but do not identify the contributors. `` We have never had any sort of a litmus test when somebody has wanted to contribute,'' <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> said in an interview, adding that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> had 168,000 donors this year and 379,000 since it was founded. He said he would continue to head <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> as an `` incubator for new ideas,'' and that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English had been given mailing lists and would be able to operate independently. Supporters of Proposition 106 say it would unify the state and help minorities join the mainstream more quickly. Critics say it would disrupt the operation of civil courts, English-proficiency classes, and tourism and commerce with other countries. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English, through its campaign-finance arm, has contributed $ 160,603, or about 97 percent of total contributions in support of Prop 106, according to the latest available records. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Meek </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> opponents of Prop 106, said he viewed the <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> resignation as `` largely cosmetic'' because <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> retained control of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and because he was being replaced as chairman of U.S. English by board member <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION>, `` one of his strongest supporters.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English was founded in 1983 by <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> and former Sen. S.I. <PERSON> Hayakawa </PERSON>, R-Calif.
