<HEAD>Investigators Expect More Money Laundering Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators are looking into the affairs of 40 banks across the country and expect to turn up `` a couple'' more that have engaged in money laundering for drug dealers, Customs Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said today. `` It's just amazing what happens when you turn over a rock as big as this,'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show. `` We've got our agents in 40 banks around the country, as well as this bank in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. There are British agents in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> agents in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, and there's just voluminous material, all of which is more or less bearing out what we expected to find,'' he said. `` We expect to see a lot of indictments coming out of this,'' he said. The indictment last week of a bank holding company has not halted such money handling, <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. `` We're looking at as much as $ 50 billion a year that is laundered overseas. So this bank, at best, could have laundered only a hundredth of that.'' `` We have n't put a stop to it yet,'' he said. But the indictment of the Florida-based <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> is `` a very important part of a cure.'' `` No doubt there are other banks like this,'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> went on. `` There is $ 50 billion that someone has to launder, one bank ca n't do the job As to whether there are other banks that know they're doing this and are doing it intentionally, I really ca n't give you that answer `` We've got a lot of investigations; we'll probably turn up a couple.'' The charge in this case is that the bank knew what it was doing, that it knew it was dealing with drug money and that it was intentionally laundering the proceeds, he explained. Why would a bank do that, he was asked. `` Banks want the money,'' he observed. Altogether, 85 defendants have been indicted in the investigation. Indictments were returned in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. In addition, arrest warrants were issued in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in the case involving the laundering of money for the powerful Colombian drug cartel. Money laundering is the process of transferring money obtained illegally between businesses or banks in order to obscure its origin and to make it appear to have been earned in a legal manner.
