<HEAD>Laureate Says Economics `A Way of Helping People'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Allais </PERSON>, described as the man who shaped thinking about economics and the state in postwar <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, said today he had given up hoping he would win the Nobel Memorial Prize for Economic Science. `` I've been mentioned so many times before I just did n't think I would get it,'' <PERSON> Allais </PERSON>, 77, said at his apartment in the suburb of St. Cloud. Colleagues said <PERSON> Allais </PERSON>, trained as an engineer, changed fields to economics after a visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during the Depression, when he saw factories idled and men out of work. `` My motivation when I was young was an idea of being able to improve the conditions of life, to try to find a remedy to many of the problems facing the world,'' <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> told a group of reporters. `` That's what led me into economics. I saw it as a way of helping people.'' <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> was working at his home when he received the news he had won. `` It was completely unexpected. It was just mindboggling,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swedish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, which awards the prize, said <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> was chosen `` for his pioneering contributions to the theory of markets and efficient utilization of resources.'' Although little-known outside <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> was extremely influential at home, where senior officials in key government ministries and state-owned industries have enormous economic power. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Ecole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> _ from which <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> officially retired nine years ago, while continuing his research and writing _ said the new laureate had a decisive effect on economic thinking for more than two decades. `` He was the mentor for everyone involved in the economy in postwar <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> between 1945 and 1968, all the people who were in charge of the biggest enterprises and of the state planning apparatus,'' <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said. Within the world of French economic thought after World War II _ in which leftists and rightists agreed the state should play a major role in the economy _ <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> established a place for reliance on market forces. He worked on `` a system of definition of prices which would permit the economy to function at its best,'' <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Allais </PERSON>'s work provided `` a very strong base for those opposed to government direction of the economy,'' said <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautman </PERSON>, scientific director for human sciences at <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Allais </PERSON> said he hoped the Nobel Prize would allow him to continue his work, even though he is past the official retirement age. `` I'm happy to have the Nobel Prize to show how absurd this situation is,'' he said. `` It's amazing that politicians think it's normal that they should not retire, while they think it's normal to push scholars into retirement.
