<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, striving to regain the initiative in the closing weeks of the presidential campaign, pledged today that during his first four years as president `` we'll turn that trade deficit back into a trade surplus.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reminded his audience at <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> that Wednesday is the first anniversary of Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash. `` And remember why it happened?'' he asked. `` The trade deficit had soared. Republican policies of borrow and spend and borrow and spend had done the damage. `` Interest rates were going up to attract the foreign bankers we needed to buy our massive federal debt and the speculative bubble burst _ as it always does.'' Campaigning in the industrial <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was fighting to overcome the impression that Republican rival <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was surging to an insurmountable lead and that their race was virtually over. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his top aides disputed a new national poll which said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a 17-point lead over the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. Campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> called reporters' attention to another poll published in the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> which showed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> trailing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by seven points. In his <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> stressed the differences he perceived between the vice president and himself. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to help the people who already have it made,'' he said. `` I want to make every American a full shareholder in the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream ... `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cares about the people on Easy Street. I care about the people on Main Street. He's on their side. I'm on your side.'' The Democratic nominee said that in the year since the stock market fell by 500 points, neither <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> nor the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had done anything to correct the underlying causes. `` We've got to end the Republican rainbow coalition of red ink for our children, pink slips for our workers, greenmail for sharp operators on Wall Street and golden parachutes for top corporate executives,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said that in its first four years, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration `` turned two generations of trade surpluses into the world's largest trade deficit _ and cost our workers 5 million jobs. `` In the first four years of the <LOCATION> Dukakis-Bentsen </LOCATION> administration we'll turn that trade deficit back into a trade surplus and reclaim those jobs for American workers,'' he said. `` That's our goal _ to eliminate the trade deficit in four years. It'll take hard work. We have to reduce the budget deficit. We'll do it.'' Monday night in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told a predominantly black audience that the Democrats have just three weeks to 21 days to `` mobilize our forces ... to reach out to our neighborhoods'' before the Nov. 8 election showdown. Earlier in the day, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> learned of the new <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> survey giving <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a 17-point lead, and said `` this business of polls is really having a terrible effect'' on the campaign. `` I can only tell you that there are other polls that say very different things about where we are and where the race is,'' the Democratic nominee said. Conceding that he is the under