<SECOND>PM-Prenatal Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Urges Greater Effort to Care For Pregnant Women</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs graf 3, The committee, to expand quote for clarity and
inserts grafs 4-10 to update with quotes from news conference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal panel recommended today that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> get serious about ensuring the health of its newborn citizens _ if for no better reason than to save money. Noting that more than $ 3 is saved for every dollar spent on prenatal care, the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> said government health officials _ federal and local _ should seek out pregnant women to make sure they get care they and their babies need early on rather than wait for frail and diseased infants to be born. The committee to study outreach for prenatal care referred to a 1985 institute study that calculated `` that each dollar spent on providing more adequate prenatal care to low-income, poorly educated women could reduce total expenditures for direct medical care of their low birthweight infants by $ 3.38 during the first year of life.'' <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lashof </PERSON>, chairman of the committee, said at a news conference today that expanding Medicaid to cover all poor, pregnant women would cost an additional $ 875 million by 1993. `` But the most important fact is we would be saving $ 3 for every dollar spent, so what we really need to be doing is calculating the net savings,'' she said. Using that formula, the Medicaid expansion `` should result in net savings of $ 2.5 billion,'' she said. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a committee member, said he is very optimistic that improvements will be made in prenatal care programs because `` if anything gets attention, it's dollars and cents.'' `` I just do n't think this nation is going to go on taking care of handicapped infants when we can prevent the handicaps with proper prenatal care,'' said <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lashof </PERSON> is on the faculty of the school of public health at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> is an obstetrics and gynecology professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> medical school in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. The survey said the health problems encountered by a significant portion of newborns includes `` a set of financial barriers ranging from problems in private insurance and Medicaid to the complete absence of health insurance.'' Among its recommendations, the committee called for the nation to `` adopt as a new social norm the principle that all pregnant women _ not only the affluent _ should be provided access to prenatal, labor and delivery, and postpartum services appropriate to their need.'' Recent federal legislation authorizes states to provide prenatal care under Medicaid for families whose income is up to 185 percent of the federal poverty line _ or more than $ 15,000 a year for a family of four. However, it is left to the states to decide whether to implement the option, which would result in a one-for-one match in federal dollars. Without referring to that new state option directly, the <ORGANIZATION> IOM </ORGANIZATION> survey said, `` Too often, communities organize outreach to help women over and around major obstacles to care rather than removing the obstacles themselves. To fund outreach in isolation and hope that it alone will accomplish major improvements in the use or prenatal services is naive and wasteful.'' The panel concluded that the solution is action rather than more study. `` The committee specifically urges that no more research be conducted to demonstrate the importance of financial and other institutional barriers to care,'' the report said. `` The committee ... recommends that the current practice of securing funds for services under the guise of research cease.'' It said the president, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and other national leaders must `` commit themselves openly and unequivocally to designing a new maternity care system _ or systems _ dedicated to drawing all women into prenatal care and providing them with an appropriate array of health and social services throughout pregnancy, childbirth, and the postpartum period.''
