<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The disappearances and mutilations of up to 30 cats have distressed residents in a city neighborhood, but police suspect that `` crazy kids'' rather than a cult are responsible. `` It really has bothered us,'' said <PERSON> Vicky </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusk </PERSON>. `` We do n't want children finding mutilated animals.'' Twenty-five to 30 cats have disappeared since late spring, said <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusk </PERSON>, one of about 300 residents of the <LOCATION> Surrey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> neighborhood who attended a special town meeting Monday night. `` My cat has been missing since July and my sister has one missing.'' Police department Capt. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said 12 cat carcasses have been found. Parts of dismembered cats appear to have been left in places where they will be spotted easily, Mrs. <PERSON> Lusk </PERSON> said. Residents are `` finding parts of them on open land, in the park, on the golf course,'' she said. `` It definitely is not a coyote or other animal ... the heads have been cut off or they have been cut in half,'' she said. `` Somebody has been doing this.'' <PERSON> Lynda </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION>, said she has received several calls from pet owners in <LOCATION> Surrey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> who reported their cats missing. Her organization has posted a $ 500 reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction of those responsible, she said. <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Police Det. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Smart </PERSON> told the residents at the meeting there was no evidence to link the disappearances and dismemberings to any cult or to suggest that the culprits could attack people. `` We have n't seen ... -LRB- or -RRB- heard of children be