<FIRST>r w AM-GarbagePoll     10-18 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garbage Poll,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey on Where To Dump the Trash: `Not in My Back Yard'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are increasingly reluctant to tolerate landfills near their homes but have n't really faced the problem of what to do about all that garbage, according to a poll commissioned by waste-handling companies. The poll results, released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, were taken from telephone interviews with 1,500 randomly selected adults in February, telephone interviews with 500 `` opinion leaders'' in March and face-to-face interviews with another 1,500 people in July and August. The February survey found that 30 percent of respondents would favor building new landfills in their communities to handle garbage and trash, while 62 percent were opposed. The remainder were undecided. Opposition was about the same _ 65 percent, in the summer poll, but those in favor had dropped to 20 percent. <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserstrom </PERSON>, public affairs director of the association, said that even if half the nation's garbage were recycled in five years, `` the remaining garbage would exceed our landfill capacity'' without new landfills or incincerators. The July-August survey found that 33 percent favored state or federal boards that could override local opposition to new facilities, and 46 percent opposed. `` I was surprised'' that support was as high as a third, <PERSON> Wasserstrom </PERSON> said. Among opinion leaders, 57 percent favored such boards and 40 percent opposed. When incinerators that can sell energy to hold down costs are matched against landfills, incinerators win _ but people still do n't want incinerators, according to the poll. Forty-seven percent of the sample opposed such `` waste-to-energy'' plants in the community, and 36 percent were in favor. `` People's attitudes about garbage disposal are highly contradictory,'' <PERSON> Wasserstrom </PERSON> said. `` A large majority of the population would like to believe recycling is the answer.'' Yet many respondents `` correctly indentified 25 to 50 percent as a realistic range'' that could be recycled. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON>, director of resource recovery programs for the association, said he had discovered a `` NIMEY'' _ `` Not in my election year'' _ to go along with the well-known `` NIMBY'' response _ `` Not in my back yard.'' `` What we need in this country is the political will to deal with these problems,'' <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> said. Seventy percent of the February sample and 84 percent of the summer group said recycling could `` solve much of the solid waste disposal problem.'' When those polled were asked how much could be recycled, the median answer was 44 percent _ half named a percentage above 44 percent and half named one below. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has estimated that 10 percent of the annual stream of 230 million tons of garbage and trash is recycled currently, with another 5 percent incinerated. The agency hopes to cajole and persuade state and local governments into making that 25 percent in 1992. The waste association represents 2,500 companies that handle half the nation's household waste and 95 percent of its industrial waste. It has conducted polls on garbage questions for several years. For a poll of 1,500 people, the margin of error is about 3 percentage points either way; for a poll of 500, the margin is a little less than 4.5 points.
</TEXT>
