<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Summit,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Fifth Superpower Summit, Fitzwater Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s spokesman on Tuesday dismissed speculation of a fifth superpower summit in the waning days of the administration, saying the idea is `` completely ruled out.'' Spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the White House generally hesitates to make flat statements about future plans, but in the case of another summit, `` We have to say no possiblity.'' No plans are under way for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to meet with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> before the president quits office in mid-January, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` Yes, I think it is completely ruled out,'' he said in response to a reporter's question. The superpower leaders have held four summit since they first met in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, in November 1985. Other summits were conducted in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> in October 1986, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in December 1987 and in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last May. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the two men signed a treaty eliminating their countries' intermediate-range nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> also said that comments made over the weekend by Deputy <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> were `` totally consistent'' with the administration's views on what is happening inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, in speeches Friday and Saturday, gave a gloomy assessment of current events in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has stepped up its spying activities against Americans since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power. He said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms have not brought about economic improvements and, `` I would even say it is doubtful that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> can rejuvenate the Soviet system.'' Moreover, the Soviet system is threatened by ethnic disturbances, he said. While the administration might not agree with the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> on every point, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>' comments `` quite correctly point out the things that we need to be very concerned about in dealing with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' He said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> have pointed out that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to see the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reduce its defense budget to underscore a commitment to world peace. `` We feel we do have better relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the president has good relations with Secretary General <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` But the system is the same, the country is the same and the threat is the same and we need to be quite aware of that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
