<HEAD>Two Workers Rescued After Dangling from Scaffold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two construction workers, left dangling 140 feet above a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> street when their scaffolding collapsed, were rescued unharmed Tuesday after 45 minutes in midair, the Fire Department said. The men were working on a building at the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia-Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> when a motor on the scaffold gave out, dumping both men from the platform on the 15th floor, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Loghran </PERSON>. `` When we arrived, the scaffold was hanging straight down and the workers were about 140 feet above the ground,'' said <PERSON> Loghran </PERSON>. The men were both suspended from safety ropes attached to the top of the building, he said. Firefighters moved a construction shed to allow a 100-foot rescue ladder in at the workers, <PERSON> Loghran </PERSON> said. Because the building is on a slope, the 100-foot ladder was able to reach the men, <PERSON> Loghran </PERSON> said. Firefighters loaded the men into the ladder bucket and brought them down uninjured, said <PERSON> Loghran </PERSON>.
