<HEAD>Whale Towing Delayed By Winds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON BAYS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Plagued by high winds in the <LOCATION> Shinnecock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION>, officials on Tuesday postponed plans to tow a stranded whale from <LOCATION> Peconic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> to the open ocean. They said they may try Thursday. The adolescent minke whale wandered into <LOCATION> Peconic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> last week, according to <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadove </PERSON>, the director of the Okeanos research foundation. He said the whale is emaciated from lack of food and disoriented, but is behaving normally. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Logan </PERSON>, an administrative assistant at the foundation, said winds in the inlet forced researchers to cancel the towing attempt and will likely force a postponement until Thursday. When conditions improve, divers from the foundation will attach a rope to the whale's tail and then put the animal in a harness and remove the tail rope, according to <PERSON> Sadove </PERSON>. The whale will then be attached to two <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> boats and towed into the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. The whale was first discovered by boaters in <LOCATION> Sag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> two weeks ago, and then moved into shallow waters of peconic bay. <PERSON> Sadove </PERSON> says the whale is 17 feet long and weighs five tons. This is the first whale sighted in <LOCATION> Peconic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Okeanos </ORGANIZATION>'s records, which go back to 1880
