<FIRST>r a AM-CityEconomy     10-18 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Economy,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: City Economy Survived Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's economy fared much better than expected in the year after last October's stock market crash, according to a report released Tuesday by state Comptroller <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>. `` While the securities industry clearly was hurt by the crash, the impact has been far less severe than originally forecast,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said. `` Furthermore, the rest of the city's economy has been little affected.'' The report predicted that the city will gain 35,000 jobs this year, despite post-crash predictions of job losses ranging from 10,000 to 47,000. The projected 1988 loss of 7,000 security industry jobs will be more than offset by an increase of 30,000 service jobs, according to the report. Even businesses closely tied to finance, such as law and printing, have shrugged off the impact of the crash. The report listed these signs of economic vitality: _ The city unemployment rate fell to 4.1 percent in the second quarter of the year, the lowest since 1970 _ The `` gross city product,'' a measure of economic output, posted its strongest annual growth in 20 years: 3.4 percent for the 12 months ending with June _ Retail sales and tourism are up, and the welfare caseload is down But the report warns that the city faces problems. The securities industry could lose an another 7,000 jobs next year, and there also may be a slowdown in employment in the real estate and banking industries. The report also noted that the 35,000-job increase for 1988 is smaller than the figure for each of the four previous years, and that many of those still employed in the security industry have taken pay cuts.
</TEXT>
