<HEAD>Bush Says America Must Stand Tough Against Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SKOKIE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Bush speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Bush later; DELETES last 2 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, speaking where <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> gave his famed `` iron curtain'' speech 42 years ago, declared today the barriers surrounding the Soviet bloc are rusting but that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must still stand tough against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> invoked the British statesman's memory in remarks prepared for delivery at <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> popularized the phrase `` iron curtain'' in 1946 to describe the barrier of self-imposed isolation and secrecy that enclosed the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after World War II. Noting his widening lead over Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in pre-election polls, the Republican nominee said both <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> and former President <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> knew that `` no election was over until it was really over. ` `` There are undecided voters out there,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` The race is close in many states. No votes can be taken for granted, and I'm not taking any votes for granted I will continue to campaign as an underdog.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not include any attack or mention of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in his speech today, which quoted at length from Churchill's speech at <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION>. `` The iron curtain still stretches from <LOCATION> Stettin </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Trieste </LOCATION>. But it's a rusting curtain,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The vice president said `` there is a new hope of change'' in Eastern bloc countries, but it would be wrong to conclude that the Soviets were deterred from aggression by their preoccupation with economic troubles. `` The Soviets are restrained by their own troubles, But they are also restrained by our strength, our ability to deter aggression, the unity of the democracies,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strength made possible the signing last year of the treaty calling for destruction of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet medium-range nuclear missiles. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said similar reductions aimed at balancing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet convention arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` will be a high priority for me.'' On Monday in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION><LOCATION> , </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, the vice president stumped for Jewish votes in the heavily Jewish suburb of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that was wrenched a decade ago by a battle over a neo-Nazi march. Speaking in a driving rain at an outdoor memorial to Holocaust victims, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the Nazi slaughter of 6 million Jews in world War II was `` an evil far more vast than any in human history.'' But he said the memorial offers `` hope for the persistence of Jewish dreams and for the promise of Jewish lives yet unlived.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> later had time to comment on his surge in the polls, including a new <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll showing him ahead of his Democratic opponent by 55 percent to 38 percent. `` We have three weeks to go from this very minute,'' he told a rally at the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Page </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellyn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` And I am running as if I were 10 points behind. I'm not going to let up.'' In <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, where he spent the night, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` Run like you're 17 points behind.'' Today <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was traveling to <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, for a foreign policy speech. <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> is where the late <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> introduced the phrase `` iron curtain'' to refer to the Soviet bloc countries in 1946. Continuing attacks on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as weak on foreign affairs and defense, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign was planning to air a new ad using footage from a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign appearance that backfired on the Democrat: his test ride in a tank. An ad that was released over the weekend suggested <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be best able to deal with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` This is no time to train somebody in how to meet with the Russians,'' the ad says. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> had no information on a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> report today that the campaign was tentatively planning to spend more than $ 15 million of its $ 30 million-plus advertising budget in three states. The three states are <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. While in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention the turmoil that occurred 10 years ago when a neo-Nazi group planned a march in the community. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> successfully fought efforts by the community to block the march, but the white supremacists decided to hold it in a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> park instead. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign gave reporters no chance to get close enough to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to ask him his views on that case or the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> involvement. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been relentless in attacking <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, a group <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> faults for far-left positions. Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said that in a longer speech that was cut short because of the rain, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had intended to mention the controversy, in which he agreed with the <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION> government. But she said he had not intended to mention the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>. In remarks pared down to just a few minutes, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was `` committed to the survival of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' `` We must keep that strategic partnership, and then we must maintain that deterrent that comes of military and diplomatic resolve,'' he said. In his earlier defense speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pledged to reform the Pentagon procurement system to cut waste.
