<HEAD>Peyote Use OK in Indian Ceremonies, Oregon High Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The use of the hallucinogenic drug peyote in Indian religious ceremonies is protected by the federal constitution's guarantee of religious freedom, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The decision involves two former <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> drug counselors who were fired and denied jobless benefits for using peyote during Native American Church religious ceremonies. In today's ruling, the high court expanded its 1986 decision in which it said denying jobless benefits to the two men violated their constitutional rights to freely practice their religion. The state had appealed the earlier ruling to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which sent it back to the state court for a definitive ruling on whether peyote could be legally used in religious ceremonies in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> under state criminal law. Peyote is a cactus that contains mescaline, a hallucinogenic drug that's illegal in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. Possession of the drug is a felony. Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, in oral arguments before the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year, said the state has constitutional authority to impose a ban on all uses of peyote. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> also argued that to permit religious use of that drug would open the door to all kinds of religious drug exemptions to be claimed in criminal trials. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in today's decision, noted that <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> laws against the possession of controlled substances, including peyote, `` make no exception for the sacramental use of peyote.'' At the same time, the court said that the `` outright prohibition of good faith religious use of peyote by ad