<HEAD>Giant Shrimp Found In Waters From S.C. To Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists and shrimpers are closely watching to see how some giant shrimp that escaped from a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> research facility will affect the native crop. The shrimp, scientifically called the Penaeus monodon but carrying nicknames such as the giant tiger, have been found in commercial nets from <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Augustine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> `` This will be very interesting to watch,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobkin </PERSON>, a professor of biological sciences at <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` But certainly it is not desirable for exotics to be loosed on nature, even though this is a nice shrimp.'' The exotic shrimp, native to the waters of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, weigh up to one-quarter pound each and reportedly taste good. But some shrimpers are concerned that they might eat native shrimp and carry contagious diseses. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>, a commercial shrimper who manages the <ORGANIZATION> Bryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisherman </ORGANIZATION>'s Coop on the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> coast, said boats docking at his facility have landed about 15 of the giant tigers since August. <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> said he notified researchers with the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> because he wanted more information about the alien shrimp. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Waddell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mariculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bluffton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, from which the shrimp escaped, said the giant tigers were certified disease-free by the Hawaiian hatchery that supplied them. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, a biologist with the Marine Extension Center who began documenting catches and doing research on the giant tigers in August, said the imported shrimp are not as inclined to eat their own kind as native white shrimp. Manager <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Waddell </PERSON> center imported more than 700,000 quarter-inch tiger shrimp this spring and used them to stock three artificial ponds on the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast, including a pond at the <LOCATION> Bluffton </LOCATION> facility, where researchers conduct mariculture experiments. Although the center and private mariculture operations have successfully raised imported <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> ocean shrimp in their ponds in past years, this was the first year any of the giant tiger shrimp were brought to the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast, he said. At the <LOCATION> Bluffton </LOCATION> center, fine-mesh screens were installed in the floodgates of dikes surrounding the pond to prevent the shrimp from migrating to tidal waters, <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said. `` But the shrimp apparently went around the screens,'' he said. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said he has no idea how many of the 100,000 shrimp initially stocked in the center's pond found their way to open waters. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> first realized that some of the giant shrimp had escaped when a few showed up in a drainage canal leading from the pond to a tidal waterway, he said. `` Then we got a call in late July from a shrimp boat captain who said he had an odd-looking shrimp,'' <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said.
