<FIRST>r p AM-ToxicInitiatives     10-18 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Initiatives,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters in Washington State To Decide Rival Toxic Waste Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Environmentalists are dueling with business and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state over rival ballot measures that each side claims is the best way to clean up toxic waste sites. Environmental groups back Initiative 97 which would give the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecology </ORGANIZATION> unilateral authority to order a site cleaned up, impose stiff fines and pursue criminal sanctions against polluters who balked. But rival ballot measure 97B, backed by the business community and most state legislators, would allow polluters time to negotiate a clean-up plan. Supporters say 97B's strength is it permits the state and industry to clean up sites together, with industry bearing most of the expense. If 97B passes, it will affirm a toxic waste cleanup statute enacted a year ago. Initiative 97 would raise an estimated $ 63.4 million to $ 68 million through a seven-tenths of 1 percent tax on toxic substances, including gasoline and other refined oil products. Measure 97B would raise an estimated $ 51 million to $ 56 million by means of a eight-tenths of 1 percent tax on hazardous substances. This tax also would apply to refined oil products, but unlike Initiative 97, would exempt refined products exported to other states. The bulk of revenues generated by either measure would go towards pay overhead, administration and enforcement of the law, state officials said. Backers of each measure, which will be on Nov. 8 ballots, claim that theirs is tougher on polluters. `` The 97B proposal creates a set of bureaucratic hoops through which liable persons can make DOE jump before it can get a site cleaned up,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a Boston-based specialist on toxic waste clean-up laws. `` No other state -LRB- with toxic waste clean-up laws -RRB- has such a convoluted response as that of the 97B proposal.'' But supporters of 97B argue that the law's cooperative approach is its strength and the reason that, ultimately, it is tougher than 97. Sen. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreidler </PERSON>, D-Olympia, who helped draft the measure before it became law at a special legislative session a year ago, said 97B envisions that polluters themselves will pay more than 70 percent of negotiated clean-up costs, while only a small part of the cost will come from the law's special tax on possessors of hazardous substances. Initiative 97, meanwhile, would rely on a similar tax as its primary source of clean-up funding, <PERSON> Kreidler </PERSON> contended, even though expected revenues would not begin to cover the estimated $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion needed to cleanse as many as 400 waste sites in the state. Initiative 97, <PERSON> Kreidler </PERSON> said, assumes that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecology </ORGANIZATION> will `` use the -LRB- tax -RRB- fund for clean up, and then litigate to recover the costs.'' He said litigation to recover the balance would mean costly delays at best and possibly no money at the end. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bricklin </PERSON>, a main spokesman for the Initiative 97 campaign and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, countered that Initiative 97 `` also relies heavily on voluntary clean-ups. It is just that ours has a significant stick attached to it to ensure that responsible parties step forward to clean up the sites without forcing the state to go to court.'' Supporters of 97B, led by aerospace, oil and timber interests, have raised $ 800,000 for their highly visible campaign featuring billboards, mass mailings and TV advertising. Initiative 97 backers, meanwhile, have raised only $ 196,000, and campaigners acknowledge that 97B's greater financial resources put their initiative at a disadvantage. Despite the heated debate, some here believe that either measure would leave the state with a sound toxic waste policy. `` We are not at a crossroads in state environmental policy,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Goltz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> lawyer and former head of the state Ecology Division of the attorney general's office. `` What is left for voters to decide this November are relatively minimal modifications of the approach the legislature already adopted,'' he said. `` Either the initiative or the alternative would establish a sound, pro-environment toxic waste policy for the state, without undue burden on industry.''
</TEXT>
