<HEAD>CBS' News Chief Says Media and Public to Blame for Election
Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Coverage of the presidential election by sound bite is n't serving the public, but what the news media is dishing out appears to be what the public wants, new CBS News President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, appearing before television critics for the first time since he moved over from <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in July, said he did not know how to steer the public's attention, and thus the news media's, away from glib quotes and flashy images and onto important issues. `` I sort of sense an unwanting to know among the public. I mean, the public is buying the flag factories and Pledge of Allegiance and card-carrying this and card-carrying that,'' said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. `` I suppose we have n't done our job well if we do n't keep beating on them that they should n't be paying attention to that, they should be paying attention to other things. `` I fault us, I expect, for being members of this same public and not being willing to put on the hair shirt and say, ` Sit down, we're going to talk to you about the federal deficit.''' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, 52, is the first outsider to head <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. He had been at <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> for 11 years and had served as executive vice president since 1986. Before entering the news business, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> worked in Democratic politics, as secretary to former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> in the 1970s, and in the 1960s as administrative assistant to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said he supported `` CBS Evening News'' anchor <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>'s decision not to serve as a panelist on the second presidential debate, calling the forum `` contrived. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> was a panelist on the first presidential debate in September and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> was one of the questioners for the vice presidential debate earlier this month. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said the League of Women Voters was right to withdraw its sponsorship of the second presidential debate because of the numerous restrictions insisted upon by each candidate. `` Those debates were a contrivance,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. `` ... He -LRB- Rather -RRB- was uncomfortable with it, I was terribly uncomfortable with it. ... I think it was the right decision, absolutely the right decision.'' As far as <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>' regular programming, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> indicated strong devotion to `` CBS This Morning,'' the 11-month-old morning talk show, and to `` 48 Hours,'' a prime-time documentary series that premiered last season. He hedged on the future of `` West 57th,'' the on-again, off-again newsmagazine that has languished in a Saturday night time period since last season. But the news division has no alternative time period to suggest, and the network is not anxious to replace it with more expensive entertainment programming, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. `` It's not in stone,'' he said. `` ` 48 Hours' is in stone. The morning is in stone.''
