<HEAD>Predict Chemical Weapons Spread, Including Syria, Libya</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 4 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s effective use of chemical weapons against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is likely to encourage other countries to acquire them, and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> probably have already done so, according to a report released Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> may also have secret arsenals of nerve agents and other chemical weapons. In its annual survey, the London-based institute also said Soviet conventional forces remain poised for swift attack, with no sign of a winding down or switching to defensive positions despite talk of change since <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took office. In the past year, the numerical superiority of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>'s conventional forces over those of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance has, if anything, increased, the survey said But the institute said a raw count of weapons and manpower _ including a 2-1 <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact advantage in main battle tanks _ was too simplistic to judge which side really has the edge. The report refused to offer any overall judgment of the state of the NATO-Warsaw Pact conventional balance. In long-range nuclear weapons, a six-percent increase by both superpowers to some 14,600 American and 11,700 Soviet warheads left them equally matched. `` Despite this numerical disparity, we judge that equivalent strategic parity remains,'' said institute deputy director Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>. The survey was gloomiest about chemical weapons. It said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could attack the entire <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> area with chemical and biological weapons sprayed from aircraft or delivered by missiles, free-fall bombs or artillery shells. It also indicated that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of mustard gas and other nerve agents likely served as an advertisement, particularly in Third World countries, for the weapons, which have been condemned internationally as inhuman. `` The role of chemical warfare in the Iran-Iraq war ... is more likely to be seen as an encouragement to the future use of chemical weapons in other regional conflicts, than as a discouragement,'' the survey said. <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Heisbourg </PERSON> said unless an international conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> next year bolsters a 1925 protocol banning chemical weapons in any war, more countries will acquire them. The protocol has been undermined by use of chemical weapons in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war and by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> using them against Kurdish rebels this year. Attempts to get a global ban on such weapons are stalled. `` Unless the authority of the protocol is internationally reaffirmed ... I suspect that other countries which theoretically could produce chemical weapons will be tempted to do so,'' said <PERSON> Heisbourg </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> are strongly suspected,'' he added. `` <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has used chemical weapons against <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> in 1966 so there is a presumption there, while <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is closing no options ... with the perceived Syrian threat.'' Only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> acknowledge having chemical weapons. But the institute said up to 20 more countries, including <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, were suspected of stockpiling or preparing to produce the weapons. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> says it has a 50,000-ton chemical weapon stockpile _ one-sixth of the total estimated by Western analysts. The institute supported the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' resumption last year of production of binary weapons _ separate agents that are lethal only when combined, saying that without a global ban `` deterrence is the only policy for <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to follow.'' On <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact-NATO conventional forces, the survey showed the main disparity in battle tanks: 22,200 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> tanks deployed from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to the Urals, facing 53,000 of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. Globally <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> had 33,600 tanks and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact 68,900, compared with 30,500 and 68,300 the previous year. Soviet conventional forces exceeded defense needs and were `` configured and deployed in a fashion which favors high-speed, short-warning, offensive -LRB- or counteroffensive -RRB- operations.'' Meanwhile, with only <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> increasing defense spending in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> may be hard-pressed to maintain its present forces, the survey said. `` Any significant response to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> calls for increased European burden-sharing seems unlikely,'' The institute also said <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> may now be able to make nuclear weapons. Four other officially non-nuclear powers _ <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ have long been suspected of having atomic weapons or being able to produce them.
