 Democrat <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> was reluctant to take on Republican Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> again after losing to him in a landslide two years ago. But now a costly battle over ethics has turned the race for governor in the nation's tiniest state into a surprising cliffhanger. <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON>, a multimillionaire communications executive who lost by a 2-to-1 margin in 1986, has capitalized on news stories about <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> family land deals, about <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> administration handling of a major unfinished bridge project, and about state contracts for trash hauling and engineering services awarded to <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> campaign contributors. <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON>, who said early private polls showed him as much as 50 points behind, has drawn even and surged ahead in some recent surveys. A telephone survey of 400 likely voters conducted for local radio and television stations after an Oct. 10 debate between <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> showed the race too close to call, with <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> receiving 40 percent support and <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> 38 percent, well within the poll's 5 percent margin of error. A week earlier, <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> had an 11 percentage point lead. `` What I've noticed is that neither candidate has made much of an inroad into the 15 percent undecided,'' said <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON>'s campaign manager, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Haupt </PERSON>. `` From what I've seen, the undecideds break fairly heavily for the challenger. They want a change. ... `` I expect finally, the last week, people will start choosing sides.'' <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON>'s support, moreover, remains soft. One poll showed that about two-thirds of those surveyed said they were voting more against <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> than for <PERSON> Sundlun </PE