ns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, mismanaged that company to a loss; `` ran -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Outlet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- into the ground'' before selling it to a company that later closed the chain; and was involved in the Executive Jet Aviation scandal of the 1970s that led to the downfall of the <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> denies those charges. `` I have seen my reputation sought to be destroyed in 30 seconds _ 30-second spots,'' he said. The barrage of ads and counter ads is costly. Recent campaign finance reports show that in September, <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> spent $ 577,000, incuding about $ 90,000 per week for televison and radio. <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> lent his campaign $ 495,000 during that period and has provided most of the $ 1.4 million in loans outstanding, <PERSON> Haupt </PERSON> said. The campaign had about $ 10,000 left, but <PERSON> Sundlun </PERSON> was prepared to loan more, <PERSON> Haupt </PERSON> said. From July through mid-October, <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON>'s campaign reported spending more than $ 1 million, including more than $ 100,000 per week in television and radio ads beginning in September. Most of his money came from individual and corporate contributions, along with a $ 200,000 bank loan. Observers agree the race is one of the most expensive in memory in this state, which has a population of just under 1 million and is geographically the nation's smallest.
