<HEAD>Nobel Prize Winner Cites Small-Town Beginnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONDON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nobel Prize-winning scientist <PERSON> Linus </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON> traces his scholarly triumphs to his childhood years in <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, a small north-central <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> community where his father ran a drug store. `` I may very well owe a lot of my understanding of the nature of the world to the introduction I received in Condon,'' <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON>, 87, said at the dedication of an airport that bears his name. About 200 people huddled out of the wind in a hangar at newly named <ORGANIZATION> Condon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> Airport-Pauling Field on Saturday to hear Pauling speak. The <ORGANIZATION> Gilliam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> presented <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON> with a brick from the walkway in front of <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION>. A red cross and nickel are imbedded in the brick. <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON>, who was 5 when his family moved to <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> in 1906, said he remembered the brick, especially the nickel, because, `` I could never get it out.'' He reciprocated with a cut glass bowl saved from the drug store by his sister in a 1908 fire. Historical society president <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamerrer </PERSON> said the bowl would be displayed in the society's museum. <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON>'s father was a manufacturing pharmacist who prescribed and mixed medicines and salves on a marble slab in his store. Fifty-six years ago, <PERSON> Pauling </PERSON> published `` The Nature of the Chemical Bond,'' a book regarded today as a science classic. He won his first Nobel Prize in 1954 for chemistry, and won the 1962 Nobel Prize for peace for efforts to ban nuclear testing. His nuclear test ban petition was signed by more than 9,000 scientists in 44 countries. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>'s airport, originally built in the mid-1940s by local businessmen, underwent a $ 1 million renovation, including a new 3,500-foot lighted runway.
