<HEAD>`Rust Belt' Making Income Gains, But Coasts Still Prevail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Income growth in the `` Rust Belt'' manufacturing states is staging a comeback after lagging behind the national average for most of the 1980s, the government said Tuesday. The trend represents an easing in, but not an end to, a phenomenon <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration critics have labeled the `` bicoastal economy.'' The administration has pointed with pride to the six-year economic recovery, the longest during peacetime since the Civil War. However, critics say the nation's heartland has not shared in the expansion. In a report on non-farm personal income, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said, in general, states bordering the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coasts continue to have better income growth than the states in between, but the gap in the growth rates is narrowing. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, a center of the boom in computer and other high-technology industries, still leads the nation in income growth. From the second quarter -LRB- April-June -RRB- of 1987 to second quarter of this year, income grew 9.5 percent, compared with 8.7 percent average annual growth since the end of the last recession in the third quarter of 1982. New <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s growth for both periods was well above the national average of 7.7 percent in the 12 months ending in June _ the latest period for which figures are available _ and the 7.1 percent annual average for 1982-87. The growth rates are not adjusted to remove the effects of consumer price inflation, which was 4 percent in the 12 months ending in June. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachussets </LOCATION> posted particularly strong income gains of 10.7 percent and 9.9 percent, respectively, in the latest year available. But gains in manufacturing have pushed income growth in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states up to average, and growth in <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states has climbed from the middle ranks to above average. In the 12 months ending in June, growth in the <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> region, led by <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, was 8.7 percent, compared with 7.4 percent annual growth in the 1982-87 period. Growth in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region, which lagged behind during the years of the overvalued dollar and exploding trade deficit, was 7.7 percent in the 12 months ending in June, compared with 6.2 percent earlier in the decade. Meanwhile, income growth in the Far West and the Southeast has cooled a bit from above-average rates. The Southeast, part of the `` Sun Belt'' boom of the early 1980s, inched down to a 7.5 percent growth rate from 7.9 percent in 1982-87. The Far West cooled to 7.8 percent in the latest 12 months, down from 8.2 percent. The Plains states, <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> area, all dependent on either agriculture, mining, oil drilling or a combination, all showed improvement, but remain at the bottom of the list. Income growth in the Plains was 6.2 percent in the 12 months ending in June, up from 5.9 percent earlier; in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, 5.8 percent, up from 5.5 percent; and in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> area, 5.2 percent, up from 5.1 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attributed gains in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> states to strength in the manufacturing of durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, and in construction. It said the <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> region also benefited from a pickup in manufacturing. Economists had been anticipating income gains in the manufacturing `` Rust Belt'' of the nation. The drop in the value of the dollar over the last three years has made <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods less expensive on overseas markets and has fueled a boom in export sales this year. In a separate report Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said virtually every one of its 12 regional banks were reporting `` continued strength or expansion ... across a wide range of -LRB- manufacturing -RRB- industries.'' However, the report prepared for a Nov. 1 meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy makers, said `` manufacturers are becoming less optimistic about coming months.'' They've become more cautious about the first half of 1989 following a slight slowdown late this summer, the report said. Although income growth in the Southeast as a whole was down, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, by state it was mixed. Weak growth in incomes from service jobs in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and interior states more than offset strong growth in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast states of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.
