<HEAD>Trial in Ethnic Rioting Begins in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Azerbaijanis went on trial Tuesday on murder and arson charges in riots that killed 32 people and highlighted ethnic tensions. The defendants were flown in from the Azerbaijani capital of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> and taken to the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in three unmarked gray trucks. About two dozen Armenians stood silently outside the building holding copies of death certificates for the victims, many of whom were their relatives. The group later was allowed into the courtroom. Azerbaijanis went on a rampage Feb. 28 in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, an industrial city on the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>. They burned and looted buildings, hunted down Armenians and killed them, official and unofficial reports have said. Of the 32 victims, 26 were Armenians and six were Azerbaijanis, officials said. Official reports had said more than 200 people were injured, but a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency dispatch Tuesday gave a figure twice as high. Some Armenians say the death toll was much higher and have cited <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> as a national tragedy they will never forget. <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, <PERSON> Suren </PERSON> <PERSON> Arutyunyan </PERSON>, said Oct. 8 that <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> was `` an unhealed wound in people's souls.'' The rioting was sparked by a massive Armenian campaign for control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. In addition to violence, the dispute over the mostly Armenian district has triggered strikes in the southern republics of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. The two ethnic groups, of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s more than 100 nationalities, differ in culture and religion. Foreign reporters who waited outside the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> building were not allowed to attend the trial. Court officials told the reporters they need the permission of the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, but the spokesman for that agency, <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>, said the trial was not open to correspondents. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> did not say why reporters were barred. A court official, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified the defendants as ethnic Azerbaijanis and gave their names as <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhmedov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ilgam </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yavar </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dzhafarov </PERSON>. The official said each was accused of participating in the murder of one person. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said they were charged with `` organizing and and taking a direct part in mass disorders accompanied by pogroms, acts of arson and murders.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted a court official as saying dozens of witnesses would testify and that the indictment was more than 100 pages long. The death certificates held by Armenians bore pictures of the victims and descriptions of how they were murdered. Many in the group wore black and displayed buttons of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s national flag. Moving the trial to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> represented a victory for Armenian activists who had complained that previous legal cases stemming from the rioting were biased because they were conducted by Azerbaijanis on their territory. On July 8, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN