<HEAD>Soybean Oil May Provide Claimed Benefits of Fish Oil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Healthy people on a typical <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> diet may have to look no further than their salad dressing for benefits that some people are seeking from fish oil capsules, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> scientists said Tuesday. Chemist <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Emken </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the human body rapidly converts a part of the soybean oil used in some ordinary food products into the same kinds of fatty acids found in fish oil. Two men in a preliminary study consumed the soybean oil component, linolenic acid, and within a few hours their bodies had coverted it into the same omega-3 fatty acids found in fish and marine oil, <PERSON> Emken </PERSON> said. `` Think of it this way: the body can naturally make its own fish oil omega-3 fatty acids from the linolenic acid in soybean oil,'' he said in a report released by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency. The report said capsules of fish and marine oils have been `` touted by advertisers and debated by nutrionists'' as dietary supplements. In any case, the capsules, it said, have become popular with any consumers hoping to ease or prevent conditions ranging from heart disease to rheumatoid arthritis. <PERSON> Emken </PERSON> led the study at the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and was helped in the work by <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. `` Our study is the first to show that linolenic acid is rapidly converted to omega-3 fatty acids found in marine oil,'' <PERSON> Emken </PERSON> said. `` The study also provides direction for further research to learn which dietary fatty acids, including those in fish and soybeans, best meet human nutritional needs.'' Soybean oil is the only major domestic vegetable oil that contains much linolenic acid and makes up 79 percent of the vegetable fats in the average <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diet, the report said. The fats are in such foods as shortening, margarine and cooking oil as well as in salad dressing.
