<HEAD>Nearly 1,000 Expected For Southeast-Japan Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governors of seven states and about 1,000 business and government leaders from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the Southeast will meet here this week to talk about doing business with each other. They are delegates to the joint annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States-Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and its Japanese counterpart, the <ORGANIZATION> Japan-Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The groups, which foster business investment and trade between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the Southeast, held their first meeting in 1976. They alternate their yearly sessions between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. This is the first time they've met in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. `` Japanese interest is acute in the <LOCATION> Southeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Cottle </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` A two-day meeting wo n't solve the trade imbalance,'' but it has the advantage of giving leaders a chance to talk face-to-face, he said. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> are the other states represented in the association. While the states are usually in keen competition for industrial investment, for the meeting `` we need regional cooperation to pull it off. One state alone could n't stage a conference like this,'' <PERSON> Cottle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cottle </PERSON> said there's been extensive Japanese investment in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> area, but this year has brought some good news for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, as well. Since the first of the year, Japanese investment in the state has totaled more than $ 127 million, he said.
