<TEXT>
 Leftist students occupied the downtown campus building of an independent U.S.-affiliated college Tuesday to protest private education. `` Education is n't for sale, it's for everyone!'' chanted the more than 1,000 students, who also burned a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag from the balcony of the building housing a department of <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` No private university should be allowed to operate here ... we must struggle to safeguard the public character of our education system if we want to strengthen our studies,'' the protesters said in a statement. All levels of education in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, including books and accomodation are state-funded, although more than 100 private primary and secondary schools also operate. Some independent higher education institutions also exist, but degrees gained at private colleges are not recognized by the socialist government. `` These people feel that private American education does n't have the right to exist in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> because they complain that it creates a kind of elite,'' said <PERSON> Achilles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanellopoulos </PERSON>, dean of <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` They're wrong as many of our students who can not afford the fees receive financial aid, he said.
