<HEAD>Reagan Signs Call for Vietnamese Withdrawal From Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Tuesday signed with reservations a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and establishment of a free and independent government in that country. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he welcomed `` this clear statement of principles'' on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, but he disagreed with certain clauses which he feared could complicate efforts to ensure that <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> rebels never again attain power. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution stipulates that the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people be protected from the return of a <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, who, under <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> in the late 1970s, are thought to have slaughtered as many as 2 million people. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did not specify his reservations, but a White House official said the president's main problem was language in the resolution which did n't conform exactly to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants a withdrawal of Vietnamese troops in the context of an `` overall settlement'' in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, said the official, speaking on condition he not be named. The resolution did not mention the overall settlement, he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, however, said he signed the non-binding resolution because it `` makes clear that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will continue to do everything possible to assure that the Vietnamese occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is brought to an end and that effective guarantees are put into place to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> from ever again taking control of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which has installed a puppet government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, announced earlier this year that it would withdraw its 120,000 troops from the nearby country by 1990. The withdrawal, however, will leave a vaccuum. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> provides non-lethal assistance to two non-communist groups, including one headed by Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, the former chief of state. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> met last week with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Pol Pot's <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> receives support from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>.
