<HEAD>High Prices Reduce US Food Aid to Needy Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Higher commodity prices mean less grain and other items going to needy countries under the Food for Peace program in 1988-89, a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> showed Tuesday. Acting Undersecretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said allocations for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 total about 3 million metric tons of grain equivalent valued at $ 663 million. Under the program a year ago, allocations totaled 4.4 million tons of food commodities worth $ 648 million. Despite the dollar increase, higher prices for grain and some other commodities have resulted in lower tonnages for the new year. For example, a year ago about 3.8 million tons of wheat flour were allocated. In the new allocation, wheat flour totaled less than 2.5 million tons. The Food for Peace program includes titles that allow concessional sales to designated countries for up to 40 years, including an initial 10-year grace period and low interest rates. Another allows the forgiveness of debt incurred under the concessional sales, based on development carried out by the recipient countries. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said $ 139.5 million in unallocated funds has been set aside as a reserve to provide commodities `` for unforeseen needs'' during the year. Last year the reserve was $ 85.6 million. The largest allocations went to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, $ 170 million; <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, $ 80 million, and <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, $ 60 million.
