<HEAD>Women's Library Reopens After $3.4 Million Renovation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the years after it was founded in 1943, <ORGANIZATION> Radcliffe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Library </PERSON> on the History of Women in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was a sleepy place with few visitors, curators say. But with its official reopening Tuesday after a $ 3.5 million renovation, the library is sleepy no longer. After its humble beginnings in two small rooms in the basement of a building on the Radcliffe campus, the library now occupies the entire structure. Because of the interest sparked in women's studies by the feminist movement, the number of visiting researchers now numbers about 5,000 per year. The library, the only one of its kind in the nation, collects materials on women's roles and contributions from 1800 to the present. It includes a collection so varied that one can study aviatrix <PERSON> Amelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Earhart </PERSON>'s papers, research the early women's suffrage movement, peruse 5,000 cookbooks or review former first lady <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s `` Book of Common Sense Etiquette. The red-brick building in <LOCATION> Radcliffe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yard </LOCATION> houses rooms for visiting scholars, film and videotape viewing rooms for oral history projects, photography exhibits, 500 women's interest-periodicals, a planned wooden relief by sculptress <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevelson </PERSON> and the 5,000-volume <ORGANIZATION> Julia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION>, named for the famed chef `` It's like a quantum jump in the recognition that real women's issues and history are here to stay,'' said <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON>, curator of manuscripts, who has been at the library since 1971 Alongside oil portraits of <PERSON> Lydia </PERS