<HEAD>Flash Fire Damages Magellan Venus Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with fire caused by human
error; quotes; picks up 8th graf pvs, `Atlantis' astronauts...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A technician who plugged a connector into the wrong receptacle caused a flash electrical fire that did minor damage to the $ 216 million <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venus </ORGANIZATION> probe being readied for a space shuttle launch next year, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. Smoke and a 2-to-3-inch flame spurted from a spacecraft battery when the worker tried to insert the cable connector into the wrong slot Monday night, <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION> project official <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON> said. `` Technicians on the scene quickly put out the fire within a minute with a halon fire extinguisher,'' <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON> said. `` But by then the damage was done. It resulted in a short that damaged the battery and wire harness and insulation blankets near the battery.'' He termed the damage minor and estimated it would take five to seven days to get spacecraft preparation back on schedule. He said there would be no impact on the April launch date aboard the shuttle Atlantis. <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON> played a videotape made Tuesday that showed some soot damage around the battery area. The battery, he explained, was being used to run routine power system checks in the spacecraft's forward equipment module and is not part of the flight hardware He said the fire deposited `` some soot, grease and grime'' on parts of the spacecraft and that it would have to be cleaned up. He said <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION>, because of its planetary mission, has to be kept extremely contamination-free and that cleaning experts were being flown in from <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and from <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, where the craft was built. Because an electrical short was involved, <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON> said engineers were ch