<HEAD>Court Dismisses Lawmakers' Claim on War Powers Act in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court dismissed a claim by 110 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should have invoked the 1983 War Powers Resolution when <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships were sent to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last year, the court said Tuesday. A three-judge panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war had rendered the war-powers issue moot. The ruling was made by <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judges </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Wald </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> in a brief order filed Monday and made public Tuesday. The panel had been asked to review a lower court's dismissal last year of the lawsuit on the ground that it presented a political question upon which judges can not rule. The appeals court, however, dismissed the case without deciding that question. The issue in the case filed by Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowry </PERSON>, D-Wash., and 109 colleagues was whether President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should have notified <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> within 48 hours of sending <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships to escort reflagged <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> oil tankers in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last year The 1983 War Powers Resolution requires the president, in the absence of a declaration of war, to notify <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> whenever <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces are sent into hostilities. The lawmakers claimed they were denied participation in the warmaking process because <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did not submit notice. Under the resolution, the president must withdraw forces within 60 days absent a declaration or war or seek an extension from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` can claim no present injury as a result of their reduced ability to participate in a process which has been completed,'' the court said. `` Appellants' assertion of continuing injury is thus logically dependent upon their ability to demonstrate that hostilities are currently present or imminent. That demonstration can not be made,'' the court said. One of the plaintiffs, Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, D-Ore., said the court's decision `` was a disaster for the War Powers Resolution and the Constitution. `` Future presidents will have no hesitation -LRB- to ignore -RRB- the clear requirements of this law. ... As of today, the War Powers Resolution is n't worth the paper it was printed on,'' he said in a statement. The court had asked both sides to file briefs on how the cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> affected the case. Lawmakers argued in their brief that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces still faced imminent hostilities because the cease-fire between the two countries is unstable. But the court said the court could not decide the merits of that claim because it `` would require an inquiry into the likely intentions of the Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> governments'' that is `` beyond the judicial competence.''
