urt for a definitive ruling on whether peyote could be legally used in religious ceremonies in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. In arguments before the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year, the attorney general's office said the state has constitutional authority to impose a ban on all uses of peyote. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in Tuesday's decision, noted that <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> laws against the possession of controlled substances, including peyote, `` make no exception for the sacramental use of peyote.'' At the same time, the court said that the `` outright prohibition of good faith religious use of peyote by adult members of the <ORGANIZATION> Native </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> would violate the First Amendment directly and as interpreted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.''
