<HEAD>At Least Quarter-Million Sudanese Died This Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 2 grafs at end UPDATING with plane reported hit by
gunfire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s dusty paths became trails of death where an an estimated 260,000 refugees, mostly children, starved or died in the gunfire of a civil war this year, Western relief officials said Tuesday. Among the victims were 180,000 children fleeing the war with their parents, and about 95,000 could have been saved by simple medical help such as vaccination, said Cole Dodge, <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> representative of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> child-welfare organization <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>. The relief officials said most of the quarter-million people died during long treks northward toward <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> or eastward into <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> in search of safety. The officials said the refugees, of whom one in five died, suffered from lack of food or medical care after they left their home villages. `` You have to notice that exceptionally large numbers of people, affected by an accumulation of the effects of five years of war, left their homes this year. Deaths in other years have been much lower,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION>. Up to 2 million people have fled their homes in the southern battle zone since the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, led by U.S.-educated renegade army Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, took up arms against the government in 1983. The rebels, who are mostly Christian or animist <ORGANIZATION> Dinka </ORGANIZATION> tribesmen, are fighting the government dominated by Arab-descended Moslems. <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON> said dimished farming and commerce in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> since the war began have contributed to conditions that led to the high number of deaths in 1988. `` The result is staggering: 260,000 estimated deaths. And that's a conservative estimate,'' said one official, who spoke on condition of anonymity <PERSON> Haj </PERSON> <PERSON> Tayeb </PERSON>, acting commissioner of relief, said Western agencies have exaggerated the casualties. However, he said the government has no estimates on the numbers of civilians who died or were made homeless in the war. An army spokesman, who requested anonymity, said there also were no official estimates of government or rebel battlefield casualties. Western relief figures show that in 1988, 700,000 southerners walked to the northern capital of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, 150,000 to the southern town of <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>, 300,000 to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and 150,000 to the regions of <LOCATION> Kordofan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Darfur </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wannop </PERSON>, representative of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Development Program, said relief organizations must distribute the food cautiously so that it does n't fall into the hands of the rebels. The government in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> has accused some agencies of supporting the guerrillas and has expelled several organizations. The guerrillas say they control more than 90 percent of the southern countryside, but the government says it controls the main towns. The towns are restricted to most Western relief agencies, making it difficult to assess conditions there. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> announced last week it was beginning a $ 1 million airlift to <LOCATION> Abyei </LOCATION>, a refugee town of about 35,000 just north of the war zone. An estimated 3,000 residents starved or died of diseases during the summer. Up to 10,000 people were estimated to have died in the southern <LOCATION> Kordofan </LOCATION> area near <LOCATION> Abyei </LOCATION>. Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agency also was trying to charter aircraft for a relief mission to the rebel-besieged town of <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION> in the heart of the war zone. An estimated 6,000 civilians and an undetermined number of troops were reported stranded there with almost no food or supplies. But the sources said the American agency was having trouble chartering a plane, since insurance rates have soared because of rebel threats to shoot down relief planes. Another problem was obtaining military approval for the flights, the sources said. A military spokesman who asked not to be identified charged that some non-governmental Western relief organizations provide aid mainly to the rebels. A <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 was shot at on takeoff from <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION> airport Monday in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and one engine was hit, but the plane flew back to <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> on three engines and landed safely, informed sources said. The sources, speaking in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity, said Tuesday they did not know who did the shooting or how many people were on the plane, which mainly carries relief supplies to <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>, capital of the <LOCATION> Equatoria </LOCATION> region.
