<HEAD>Talks Postponed Until At Least Oct. 24</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with reax from opposition, prosecutor
investigating demonstration; church expressing concern at treatment
of former strikers; Rakowski to go to Soviet Union. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced Tuesday that talks with the opposition have been delayed until after Oct. 24, and urged its partners in the dialogue to disavow `` extreme elements'' before the talks begin. The outlawed Solidarity labor federation replied it was ready to begin talks immediately and blamed the government for the delay. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> strongly criticized anti-communist banners and slogans during a street protest in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> on Sunday and asked participants in the discussions to disassociate themselves from the protesters. Urban denied that the government was losing its will to enter the talks or putting new conditions on the discussions, which are to cover such questions as relegalizing Solidarity and economic and political pluralism. `` There are justified fears that not all the partners of the round table are being led by the same intention,'' he said. Urban said talks originally due to start Monday were delayed because church representatives who will take part wo n't return from <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> until Oct. 24 and because of remaining disagreements over who will participate. `` It's difficult to talk with those who are shouting that they want to hang communists,'' said Urban. `` In this situation, the constructive, pro-reformatory opposition has to make its decision. Either it will be willing to seek agreement, against the extreme wing, or it will get linked with the extreme elements.'' Solidarity denied any extremism on its side. `` Solidarity, by the fact that it seeks relegalization, obviously is ready to act as a legal union which accepts the constitution, and all the people participating in these talks will share the same view,'' Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said the opposition has been ready since Monday to begin. He said further delay could raise questions about the government's desire for dialogue and prolongs an `` atmosphere of hopelessness'' that he said led to the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> episode. Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> originally agreed to the talks on Aug. 31. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> then brought a halt to nationwide strikes that were <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor unrest since 1981. While refusing to give a likely date for convening the round table, Urban said officials would like discussions to begin between Oct. 24 and the Nov. 2 visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. He said the atmosphere for the talks was made worse by the Sunday march by about 700 youths in the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> port city of <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> that ended with youths throwing rocks at riot police. Official state publications and television gave heavy coverage to the incident. The state-run <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said a prosecutor was investigating. Urban said that among slogans chanted were `` Communists will hang on trees instead of leaves!'' and `` Better the coffin than the commune!'' `` I think that the organizers of this demonstration were striving for torpedoing the agreement -LRB- for talks -RRB- and for overturning the round table,'' he said. But Solidarity spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Madajska-Krasowska </PERSON> on Sunday said Solidarity activists tried to persuade the demonstrators to disperse. The youths left only after police with water cannon arrived, she said. Urban said Tuesday that `` a problem'' remained with the proposed participation of longtime Solidarity advisers <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> and <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON>. `` Gen. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s offer ... said that all who stand on the ground of socialism and the constitutional order can sit at this table,'' Urban said. `` It's difficult for <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> to fit into this category.'' The Roman Catholic Church expressed concern Tuesday night that job guarantees given workers who ended strikes in August and September were violated. The episcopate secretariat, representing <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops nationwide, said it sent a letter Monday to <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> reminding him of the guarantees of personal and employment security for strikers. Coal miners in southern <LOCATION> Silesia </LOCATION> and steel workers in the southeastern city of <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> complained that strikers lost their jobs or suffered other reprisals, the secretariat reported. In another announcement, <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said that Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> plans to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this week in his first trip abroad as head of government. Urban did not give an exact date.
