<HEAD>Bentsen Says He's Fed Up With Negative Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with UCLA speech as delivered; appearance in
Huntington Beach; EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> unleashed a snarling attack Tuesday on the Republicans for running a campaign that has turned the presidential election `` into a carnival sideshow of nonsense and negativism.'' `` We have witnessed, through the combined efforts of the Republican party and their image makers and their nominees for president and vice president, one of the most outrageous displays of negative campaigning ever seen in the history of national politics,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' running made said in a speech before more than a thousand students in a <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> auditorium. They were attending a forum on public service sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga. `` The idea of citizenship, in fact, the very idea of self-government itself, is under attack,'' the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator said `` And there is no greater violation of that trust than to turn a great national election into a carnival sideshow of nonsense and negativism.'' `` What has happened _ almost without notice _ is an utterly vicious assault of distortion and character assassination'' directed at <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he said. `` They do n't seem to mind what they say is untrue,'' he said. `` They do n't seem to mind if it's misleading. They do n't seem to care that what they do is downright mean. If it sounds good, say it. If it sells, package it. If it looks good, nominate it.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said the Democrats have at times been slow to respond to the charges. `` But I do n't think we ever imagined that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the Republicans would be so willing to debase that precious currency of our democracy.'' The Democrats have `` taken a beating from the pundits and the pollsters'' who have `` pointed to an open casket in the ground and virtually invited us to jump in.'' But <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, who had been promisng a `` give -'em hell'' campaign for days, said, `` We've got three weeks to go, there's a lot of work ahead, and there's no time for mourning because we intend to win <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> ridiculed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s statement that he believed in public service, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> philosophy preaches contempt for government and `` get while the getting's good.'' `` They do n't believe in much of anything at all when it comes to public service because they have nothing but disdain for the role government can play in the life of this nation,'' he said. `` They do n't understand the need for strong, ethical boundaries between public service and private gain,'' he said. Following the <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> forum, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> visited a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> aerospace plant in nearby <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, the conservative chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> blasted the Republican assertion that the Democrats would cut defense, recalling former <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>'s remark that to tell when the opposition was lying, watch for when they `` move their lips.'' And then <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> emerged from a mock-up of a space station to deliver a stump speech on defense and the space program. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was traveling next to a rally in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, completing a sweep of the three biggest <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> media markets in one day. Tuesday morning, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told local elected officials meeting in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> would pursue a much needed change in the nation's trade and economic relations with its allies. `` We're not going to become hewers of wood and carriers of water for the rest of the world. That's not our idea of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told the League of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Cities convention <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said the Republican administration has failed to promote <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade, and has led the nation further and further into debt to foreign countries. `` Many years ago, the famous pitcher, <PERSON> Satchel </PERSON> <PERSON> Paige </PERSON>, coined the phrase: ` Do n't look back _ somebody might be gaining on you,' `` he said. The need, he said, was for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to `` work harder and smarter than the competition.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he said, had proven `` an ability to attract and sustain high technology industries.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must continue its role in protecting its allies militarily. But, he said, it was time for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to start paying their fair share of the cost.
