<HEAD>Party Wrangle Persists; No Word on Leadership Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with meeting adjourns for night, no
announcements made. Picks up 3d graf pvs, Ten members ... with
minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> factions argued Tuesday about ethnic and social strife straining the fragile Yugoslav union but the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> ajourned for the night without making any major announcements. The session ended without a vote on personnel changes. The <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the meeting would resume Wednesday morning. Early Wednesday editions of the official newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Borba </ORGANIZATION> said many of the 200,000 Serbs in troubled <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> province were dissatisfied with the `` fruitless and marathon discussions'' by <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members and planned a protest rally Thursday in <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, the provincial capital. The committee is expected to make major personnel and policy changes in efforts to quiet demands for dismissal of leaders blamed in public protests for the nation's worst economic crisis since World War II. Ten members of the 23-man ruling Politburo, including national party chief <PERSON> Stipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON>, face a secret vote of confidence in the 162-member Central Committee. Four Politburo members are not involved in the vote because they already have promised to resign. Nine are exempt because they hold their seats as party leaders of the armed forces and of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics and two autonomous provinces. One of those exempt from the vote is <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, the populist party leader of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. His is the largest republic and the two autonomous provinces, <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, are part of it. His campaign for greater Serbian control over the provinces has split the national party leadership, pitting him against politicians who fear his standing with the people will rise at their expense. Serbs have rallied by the hundreds of thousands in recent weeks to express anger at alleged harassment of the Slavic minority by the huge ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> majority in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> region, the ancient Serbian heartland adjacent to <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. At a time of growing economic hardship, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> has found broad sympathy for his demand that sweeping leadership changes be made. Inflation is running at an annual rate of 217 percent, causing real wages to plummet, and the foreign debt currently stands at $ 21 billion. Austerity measures imposed in May have inspired strikes and protests by workers, whose average monthly wage is the equivalent of less than $ 100. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has not had strong leadership since President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> died in 1980. Each republic and autonomous province has its own government and party structure. <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> put the decentralized system and collective federal presidency in his 1974 constitution to prevent one republic from gaining sway, but the result has been ineffective government by compromise. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s activities have put him in open conflict with <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Milan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kucan </PERSON>, party chief in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, a liberal, Western-oriented northern republic. <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Greganovic </PERSON>, leader of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s official youth union, indirectly attacked <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> on Tuesday. `` Those leaders who are putting themselves at the head of discontented masses behave as if they were gifts from God,'' he said. `` They behave as if they did not come to power with the leaders they now attack mercilessly.'' <PERSON> Raif </PERSON> <PERSON> Dizdarevic </PERSON>, current head of the nine-member collective federal presidency, seemed to rebuke both <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kucan </PERSON> in backing <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON>'s call for party unity. `` The lack of unity in the leadership, multiplying of late, is a great danger for the country,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` We need accord to unite in fighting problems, without imposing some kind of hegemony over one another,'' said <PERSON> Dizdarevic </PERSON>, who threatened nine days ago to impose `` emergency measures'' if unrest continued. He did not specify the measures. In <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, a government plan to relax austerity measures for workers in profitable firms and social services foundered because deputies said proposed salary increases were too small. The International Monetary Fund, which insisted on the austerity program introduced in May, was said to have approved easing the rules for some workers.
</TEXT>
