<HEAD>Seven Teachers Arrested In Ohio Teachers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARBERTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven striking elementary school teachers were arrested Tuesday when they tried to block a van carrying substitutes from entering the school. Second-grade teacher <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Foore </PERSON> said police arrested her and six other women and put them in a police van after they draped a 30-foot-long banner across a driveway to the Memorial Elementary School in this <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION> suburb in northeast <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The banner said `` Kids Count _ Teachers On Strike For Class Size.'' The teachers were charged with disorderly conduct and released, she said. The arrests came after the <ORGANIZATION> Barberton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> rejected the school board's latest contract offer at a meeting Sunday night. The association represents 285 teachers that struck the 4,600-student system on Oct. 3. Lt. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Barberton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the women were arrested Tuesday morning after they refused to move away from the front of the van. He identified the six other women as <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> MacFarland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Aleman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Maxie </PERSON> <PERSON> Muckleroy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Fickert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paulette </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Daverey </PERSON>. `` It was very scary, most of us have never had a parking or traffic ticket before,'' Ms. <PERSON> Foore </PERSON> said. `` Elementary teachers are normally very meek and very mild and very passive. I would do it again. It's not the money, it's the class size.'' Police said Ms. <PERSON> MacFarland </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Foore </PERSON> were also arrested Monday and charged with disorderly conduct after they tried to block a van carrying substitute teachers to the same school. Ms. <PERSON> Foore </PERSON> said those arrested are scheduled to appear in <ORGANIZATION> Barberton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on misdemeanor charges Oct. 24. Superintendent <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Clemmer </PERSON> said the board has offered pay raises of 4.9 percent, 4 percent and 4.5 percent over three years. <PERSON> Violet </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, president of the association, said the teachers want a two-year contract with 5 percent raises, improved health benefits and class size limited to a maximum of 30 students.
