<HEAD>Salvador Says Central American Summit Canceled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The five Central American presidents have canceled their November summit meeting, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> gave as the reason _ `` We do n't have a concrete agenda or any positive points to offer our people.'' The meeting may be rescheduled for early December in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, he said. `` We do n't want a presidents' meeting that is an international political propaganda act, which would be counterproductive in the long run,'' <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> told reporters. The presidents of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> had agreed to meet to discuss reviving the regional peace plan they signed on Aug. 7, 1987. The plan was aimed at ending civil wars in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. A fragile truce is in place in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> but conflicts continue unabated in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>.
