<FIRST>u w AM-SEC-MarketHalts 1stLd-Writethru a0754 10-18 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Market Halts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Approves Plan for Coordinated Market Halts During Price Dives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with CFTC approval, comment from
Chicago Merc, NYSE; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs bgng, `During the;' Story
also moving on financial wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators announced approval Tuesday of an experimental plan for coordinated trading halts _ or circuit breakers _ in stock and futures markets during steep price dives. The plan, proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, provides for a one-hour trading halt across markets when the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks plunges by 250 points or more from the previous day's closing. It calls for a two-hour halt when the Dow falls by 400 points. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates the stock markets, and the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees futures exchanges, approved the one-year experiment on the eve of the first anniversary of the Oct. 19, 1987 stock crash. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's largest stock market and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is the largest market for trading stock index futures. Other markets, including the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>' over-the-counter system, are joining in the plan. Government approval is effective immediately. It is up to the exchanges to decide when the circuit breaker plan begins. `` We're ready to implement this as soon as Thursday,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` We think this is a very significant action to remedy what problems there were in the market a year ago.'' The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> did not give a specific start time, but said it would be `` very soon.'' The plan is designed to provide an orderly halt to trading before one market _ stock or futures _ breaks down, shifting all of the trading to the remaining market. It also is intended to allow time for buyers to step in and counter overwhelming sell orders. During the 1987 crash, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> plunged a record 508 points, wiping out $ 500 billion in paper wealth in a single day. Another part of the program gives individual investors, as opposed to pension and mutual funds, preference in trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> when the Dow moves either up or down by 25 points. The rule applies to orders of 2,099 shares and smaller. After the crash, many individual investors complained that their orders were shunted aside, in some cases for hours, while larger buy and sell orders from institutional investors were executed. The market halt plan is one of the key recommendations offered after the crash by a presidential task force headed by <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banker who is now <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> did not offer a specific proposal, but said some sort of `` circuit breaker'' was needed to derail a crash. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> said earlier this month that it was going along with the plan only reluctantly because it did not want to be the only market left open when all others were closed. But, <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON> argued that a pre-announced trigger for market halts could act as a `` magnet,'' pulling the market down faster. As the market approaches the trading halt limit, it could be flooded with orders from traders fearful they will be prevented from selling, he said. With the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> approval, which is effective immediately, a previous six-month experiment to curb computerized index arbitrage ends. The earlier program had imposed a so-called 50-point collar on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. When the market moved by 50 points or more, index arbitrage orders were not allowed through the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s automated trading system Index arbitrage is a form of trading designed to take advantage of momentary price discrepancies between the stocks and futures markets. It involves the buying and selling of massive orders on stocks and futures markets and was criticized for making last year's crash more precipitous. However, the collar experiment ran counter to the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> commission's finding that stock and future markets were in effect one market and that disconnecting them could be dangerous. A new rule taking the place of the collar is designed to provide more orderly index arbitrage. When the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poors </ORGANIZATION> 500 index falls by more than 12 points _ the equivalent of 96 points on the Dow _ index arbitrage orders will be shunted into a side file of the trading computer. If buy and sell orders can be matched, the trades will go through. If not, trading in individual S & amp; P 500 stocks could be halted.
</TEXT>
