<HEAD>Bush Vows to `Campaign As An Underdog' Until Election Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 20th graf, bgng, On an..., to record Springfield
appearance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Tuesday that with inspiration from <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> he would `` campaign as an underdog'' until Election Day, despite polls showing he has widened his lead over Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` No votes can be taken for granted and I'm not taking any votes for granted,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told an audience at <ORGANIZATION> Westminister </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Westminster was the scene of <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>'s famous 1946 speech declaring that a postwar `` Iron Curtain'' of secrecy and self-imposed isolation had surrounded the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the communist Eastern bloc. `` Churchill was right,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, although few Americans wanted to hear his message at the time. Several dozen protesters demonstrated outside the hall where the vice president spoke. One carried a sign reading, `` Bush Is No Churchill,'' echoing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s assertion that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> running mate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was `` no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` a rusting curtain'' separates East and West today, but that `` in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and other parts of the world, we have yet to see the full promise of Soviet change turn into change itself.'' If elected president, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, he would remain wary of Soviet intentions, even though the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership under <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is more enlightened than before. `` Now is not the time to abandon realism about what moves the <LOCATIO