<HEAD>`New' Beethoven Work Premieres Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-9 UPDATE with performance applauded, reaction.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, Cooper, who ... SUBBING 12th graf pvs,
Violin virtuoso ... to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE KATZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 15-minute piece of music that the arranger said was reconstructed from <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s last work was warmly applauded at its premiere Tuesday night but an occasional discordant note came later from the audience. The work, presented at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION>, is described as the first movement of what would have been <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s 10th symphony. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, a researcher at <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said he spent five years piecing together symphonic fragments found in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> after the German composer's death 161 years ago. `` The sketches struck me as being particularly good, even by <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s standards,'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday as the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> rehearsed for the premiere. `` Even though my completion wo n't be as good as <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>, I think the overall result has got enough really good <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> in it to make it very well worth hearing.'' Violinist Sir <PERSON> Yehudi </PERSON> <PERSON> Menuhin </PERSON>, who conducted the second half of the concert but not the movement, said: `` I think it is a valuable work. It is certainly <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>.'' Some purists disagreed. `` Calling this <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s 10h was a bad idea,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dankworth </PERSON>, a classically trained jazz composer. `` It should be named ` Excerpts and Snippets.''' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>, who described himself as a music lover, said, `` I thought it was marvelous fun, though I doubt <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> would have followed the Ninth with anything like that.'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, who wrote a book on <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s creative process while working on the musical reconstruction, said <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s plans to finish the final symphony were mentioned in a letter written eight days before his death in 1827. `` He actually offered it to the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'' of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said, `` And now they've got it, or as much as there is of it.'' Speaking as a white bust of <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> solemnly peered over the rehearsing musicians, <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> called his work `` a chance for other people to get some idea of what <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> had in mind. Knowing what the 10th symphony is like has increased our knowledge.'' The music ranges from whispery quiet sections to bold, soaring themes over its 15 minutes. <PERSON> Menuhin </PERSON>, after hearing the music for the first time at the rehearsal, said it was `` a very beautiful work.'' The 71-year-old musician called the controversy over the premiere `` rather silly.'' `` Everyone is eaten with curiosity,'' he said. Asked if the work was important, <PERSON> Menuhin </PERSON> said: `` They use the word ` important' for all kinds of sales of antiques and ` important' gold coins I think it's at least as important as that.'' Conductor <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Weller </PERSON> called the piece `` very, very interesting.'' `` It sounds like a very young, powerful <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>,'' he said after the practice session. `` Not the Beethoven you can hear in a slow moment of the Ninth -LRB- Symphony -RRB-, the <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> with one leg in another world. This is a powerful one.'' However, <PERSON> Weller </PERSON> said, he could tell which parts are the real <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>, and where <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> filled in the blanks. According to <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, two-thirds of the work was taken directly from <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s sketches, which sometimes were nothing more than a single line of notes. `` There's something of <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> in every bar,'' he said. `` You ca n't say <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> stops here and <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> starts there. In practically every bar, it's part <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> and part me.'' Orchestra members were taking the <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> brouhaha in stride. First cellist <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucknall </PERSON> said the movement `` is certainly <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>. We have n't heard this piece of music before, so of course it's important.'' `` I do n't think it's the best <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> we've ever heard,'' said violist <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Creech </PERSON>, `` but obviously it is very exciting.''
