<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ruby </LOCATION>, a royal red gem that weighs 48 carats, was supposed to sell for a record $ 15 million at auction Tuesday. It did n't. Instead, a high bid of $ 7.6 million was rejected as insufficient by the gem's owner, and the ruby _ which <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier called the centerpiece of `` the most important jewelry sale ever held in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' _ was taken off the block. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction house announced that the largest diamond ever auctioned to the public would be offered at a sale Wednesday. The 407.48-carat gem is second in size only to the 530.20-carat Cullinan I, which is set in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sceptre </ORGANIZATION> as part of the Crown Jewels. `` I'm certain this jewel will set a record price for a single precious stone,'' said <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Curiel </PERSON>, head of <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jewelry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. He refused to estimate the price. The record auction price for any jewel $ 9.31 million, the amount paid in April 19 for an 85.91-carat white diamond at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. The diamond, currently owned by two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> jewelry dealers and a jewelry retail chain in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, was purchased as an uncut 890-carat stone in August 1984 but has since been cut into a flawless stone. At <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s auction house Tuesday, about 300 people strained their necks to catch a glimpse of those who put up the multimillion-dollar bids for the <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ruby </LOCATION>. But the auctioneer's gavel slammed down a short time later to end the bidding without a sale. <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s spokeswoman, said the identity of the ruby's seller would not be revealed. `` Obviously, we're disappointed,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s jewelry department. `` This was expected to bring a record and it did n't. It was such an enormous price we were trying to get. On unique objects, it's very hard to put a price on it. Sometimes it does n't work.'' The ruby was offered in the same session as the Star of Sierra Leone Diamond No. 2, which was sold for $ 3.52 million Tuesday. The diamond is one of 11 stones cut from a 969-carat diamond discovered in the west African nation in 1972. Several <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ruby </LOCATION> bidders, who asked not to be identified, suggested that perhaps extensive pre-sale publicity about the ruby had backfired on <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. In its pre-auction report, <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> had given the Mandalay a glowing review. `` The combination of pleasant shape and proportions, fine color, transparency and luminosity, make it an exceptional gemstone,'' said a report released by the auction house. Block described the <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ruby </LOCATION> as `` the largest faceted gem known'' and estimated it would command about $ 15 million. The record price for a ruby is $ 1.9 million, paid at a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> auction in July for a 10.4-carat stone. The Mandalay Ruby is framed by 18 diamonds within a gold-and-platinum broach mounting. Small, diamond-set fleur-de-lys designs decorate the corners. The <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ruby </LOCATION>, named after the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> city near which it was mined, was brought to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1875. `` It is questionable if the <LOCATION