<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The General Assembly on Tuesday voted to accept <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s credentials by the widest margin in the six years since <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states have been making demands to disqualify the Jewish state. In an annual vote on membership in the 159-member world body, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was accepted by a vote of 95 to 41 with seven abstentions and 16 nations absent. That was 15 votes better than last year, when the vote was 80-39 with 10 abstentions. For the past six years during the credentials vote, an Arab nation has urged acceptance of all countries except <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Each year a Nordic country has proposed the Arab amendment be rejected. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s acting ambassador, <PERSON> Johanan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bein </PERSON>, called the vote Tuesday `` an impressive and very significant victory. `` In the six years in which we have had this annual ritual we see from year to year a gradual improvement,'' he said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has been condemned by many <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> members for its harsh measures in putting down the 10-month Palestinian uprising in Israeli-occupied territories. Increasingly, however, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and its members are calling for an international peace conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> involving <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and all parties to the dispute. Among the changes in voting this year were <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which voted `` yes'' to accept <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s credentials. Last year, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was absent. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which last year voted against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, this year was absent, in a tentative signal of warming intentions. Other countries who switched from `` no'' votes or absences to `` yes'' votes were <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Suriname </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. Two new `` no'' votes came from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which last year were absent. In July, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> severed its administrative ties with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and distanced itself as a player in a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace settlement. The Israeli Mission spokesman, <PERSON> Baruch </PERSON> <PERSON> Binah </PERSON>, attributed the improved vote to an atmosphere of international reconciliation, better East-West ties, greater pragmatism at the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and the increasing prestige of the world body.
