<DATELINE>OXFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A debt-ridden committee formed to promote <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> as home of the original Lone Ranger narrator on radio is about to ride into the sunset without erecting a hoped-for statue in a city park. The committee had sought to erect a statue of <PERSON> Brace </PERSON> <PERSON> Beemer </PERSON>, the original Lone Ranger radio show narrator and the fourth voice of the Lone Ranger in the 1940s, but fell far short of the $ 75,000 that would have been needed for the monument, committee members said. At what's expected to be its final meeting Thursday, the group will discuss how to dispose of its assets of about $ 3,000, said <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Wassil </PERSON>. A $ 2,000 printing bill is still unpaid, she said. The committee has already repaid $ 20,000 in debts, committee members said. In its first year, the group spared no expense in its promotion of the city, about 35 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, as home of the Lone Ranger. The committee sponsored a Super Week, held in conjunction with the Super Bowl, which was played in <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> on Jan. 24, 1982. `` We threw a three-day party like this town has never seen _ and never will again,'' <PERSON> Wassil </PERSON> said. Events included a concert by country music star <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wynette </PERSON> that cost $ 10,000. In the years following Super Week, the <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hosted other fund-raisers but none were successful, <PERSON> Wassil </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON>, an attorney who has n't given up on erecting a Lone Ranger statue, said he wo n't miss the committee. `` I've never had much faith in committees. I think the Lone Ranger would have ended up on a camel,'' <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> said he believes private funding, particularl