<HEAD>Senate Approves Bill Making VA a Cabinet Department</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 15th graf pvs bgng, `The House,' to
UPDATE with Agent Orange amendment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> granted election-year benefits to one of the nation's largest interest groups Tuesday when it approved bills elevating the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department and granting veterans the right to have courts review VA denial of benefits. Both measures were approved on voice votes. The measure creating the new Cabinet department now goes to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who is expected to sign it, while the judicial review plan must be returned to the House for approval. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also passed on a voice vote a bill granting a series of cost-of-living increases in a variety of VA payments. The House has yet to act on its version of that legislation. The Department of Veterans Affairs would be the 14th Cabinet seat and the fifth created since 1960. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the bill by voice vote Oct. 6. Backers of the change said the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> already has the fifth-largest budget among federal agencies and giving it Cabinet status will assure that the money is spent properly. The VA, with an annual budget of $ 30 billion, serves 27 million veterans and 49 million dependents or survivors. It will pay out about $ 14 billion this year in income maintenance and $ 626 million for education and rehabilitation assistance in the current fiscal year. The agency and its 240,000 employees administer about 90,000 patient beds in 534 health facilities and <LOCATION> VA </LOCATION> doctors will see about 20 million outpatients this year. It runs 109 national cemeteries and will bury 300,000 veterans in the next 12 months. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, switching the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department will cost $ 33 million over five years. Most of that will be spent on changing signs on VA buildings. The second major piece of legislation gives veterans, for the first time in 170 years, the right to ask federal courts to review VA denials of benefits. The bill creates a new `` <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>,'' and abolishes the current <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. That panel is part of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> and is now the last resort of veterans who are unhappy with decisions to reject their claims. The measure also eliminates a Civil War-era law which limits attorney's fees for veterans' claims to $ 10 per claim. That made it difficult for veterans to hire lawyers other than those provided by the VA.. Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called the measure a `` historic advance in veterans' rights The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved somewhat similar legislation on Oct. 3 by a 400-0 vote, but there were minor differences between that proposal and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> package. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill will now be returned to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for another vote. The benefits increase legislation provides that 2.2 million veterans with service-connected disabilities and 310,000 widows and orphans will receive the same cost-of-living increases paid to Social Security recipients. The House is expected to pass its own version, which would provide a specific 4.1 percent increase, according to <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` will undoubtedly concur'' with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> proposal, he predicted. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> added an amendment which could provide interim health care payments to some of the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans who were exposed to Agent Orange, a highly toxic defoliant used by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The measure provides a `` presumption of service connection,'' under which the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> would assume that two types of cancer _ non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and soft-tissue sarcoma _ were caused by Agent Orange. Veterans could receive benefits while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, which has n't finally agreed that Agent Orange caused cancers, studies the problem. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran, said Agent Orange provisions will have `` a very limited effect. `` I find it highly disturbing that those people who went to fight the VC -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> spend too much time fighting the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> back here in this country,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said. Before passage, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved, 47-15, an amendment to permit the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to offer Vietnam-era veterans flight training courses under the auspices of the GI bill. Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON>, D-S.D., the sponsor, said airline deregulation has created vacancies among pilots and there will be thousands of pilot jobs to be filled in the next decade. But critics said the program was offered on a trial basis in past years and had n't worked.
