<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wildfires were slowed Tuesday by lower temperatures and diminished winds after burning more than 7,300 acres and an exotic animal refuge and ancient Sequoia trees were put out of immediate danger. The good news came after nearly 2,000 firefighters attacked two big blazes with water-dropping helicopters and ground crews that cut fire lines around the threatened animals and trees. The Divide fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> 30 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> had burned 4,110 acres by Tuesday but stopped advancing toward the Wildlife Waystation, a shelter for 1,000 exotic animals that have been abandoned or wandered into neighborhoods. `` It's still a long-range threat,'' cautioned <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` It looks like we have survived this one well. We've made it,'' said <PERSON> Martine </PERSON> <PERSON> Colett </PERSON>, owner of the shelter. `` My face is a picture of wonderfulness.'' The lions, tigers, giraffes, jaguars, horses, alligators and other animals housed at the shelter became agitated as smoke and ashes surrounded the area and airplanes buzzed overhead, but they calmed down Tuesday as the fire slowed, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Colett </PERSON> praised the firefighters, who worked to clear an area around the shelter and set a backfire to burn brush down the mountain toward the fire, she said. The fire, started by a 10-year-old boy playing with matches, burned in inaccessible mountain terrain and was 50 percent contained Tuesday with full containment expected Wednesday evening. Two of the 1,030 firefighters battling the blaze suffered minor injuries. In the Sequoia National Forest 125 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, lower temperatures of 70 degrees and winds 3 to 10 mph aided firefighters battling a 1,900-acre brushfire that threatened 2,700-year-old Sequoia trees in the 3-square-mile Giant Forest. Firefighters quickly extinguished a flare-up Tuesday morning near the grove of trees which are considered the largest living things on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Although the trees were out of immediate danger, the threat remained. The fire, which officials believe was started by a careless camper or smoker, was 20 percent contained Tuesday but no estimate was given on full containment. Four of the 930 firefighters on the blaze suffered minor injuries.
