<HEAD>Critics Say New Agreement On U.S. Bases A Deception</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Wednesday newspaper comment and
CORRECT number of bases in 2nd graf from four to six. PICKS up 6th
graf pvs, ``We asked ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Critics accused the foreign secretary of deceiving his people for signing a new agreement o <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases, but President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said the pact enhances Philippine-U.S. relations. The accord, signed Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>, allows the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to use six military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> until 1991. `` He has sold out his country and grossly deceived his people,'' the national <LOCATION> Malaya </LOCATION> daily said of <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>. `` For these treasonous acts, he ought never to show his face again in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>.'' Critics said the accord could prompt even stronger opposition to <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-run </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller garrisons. `` The general perception is that the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> got the short end of the deal, and this perception is expected to be exploited by the anti-bases bloc to further fan the wave of anti-Americanism in the country,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Capino </PERSON> in Wednesday's issue of the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. Under the agreement, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will pay the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> $ 962 million a year for the use of the bases. The <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> had demanded $ 1.2 billion a year. `` We asked for 12 boxes of delicious apples, they gave us four small bags of peanuts,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>. He called the payment `` a publicly unacceptable compensation package certainly strengthens the hand of those who are batting for no extension after 1991.'' Senators on Tuesday debated whether the pact required their approval in accordance with a constitutional provision on international agreements, but were unable to resolve the issue and postponed discussion to a later date. `` I think many people, even those who are pro-bases, were disappointed by the outcome so that would even help our cause,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Wigberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanada </PERSON>, a leading opponent of the bases and principal sponsor of a senate bill banning the presence of nuclear arms in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The pact allows the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to maintain its policy of neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear weapons in aircraft and ships visiting the bases. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy was upheld, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said a constitutional ban on nuclear weapons on <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> territory `` is being implemented,'' since the storage of such arms here requires government consent. The Philippine constitution, approved in 1987, adopts a policy of freedom from nuclear weapons `` consistent with the national interest.'' Legal experts say the phrase falls short of an outright ban. `` The agreement reaffirms the enduring bilateral relationship between our respective countries and allows us to proceed to improve other aspects in that relationship,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said in a statement. Communist guerillas, whose demand for the removal of the bases has fanned a 20-year-old rebellion, accused the goverment of `` shamelessly selling out'' Philippine sovereignty. `` We call on the Filipino people to reject this new agreement and hold President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> accountable for this act of high treason,'' the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The accord ends a nearly seven-month review of the 1947 agreement governing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, which are the largest in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>.
