<HEAD>Alfonsin Sets May 14 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> on Tuesday called national elections for May 14 and hailed in advance what he termed `` a singular accomplishment'' in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> _ the peaceful handing over of political power. `` On Dec. 10, 1989, 61 years since the last time it happened, I will hand over the sash and cane -LRB- Argentine symbols of office -RRB- to the president who will succeed me in the honorable task of leading Argentines on the unstoppable path to progress and greatness,'' <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> said. In 1928, <PERSON> Hipolito </PERSON> <PERSON> Yrigoyen </PERSON> won national elections and replaced President <PERSON> Marcelo </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvear </PERSON>. Two years later <PERSON> Yrigoyen </PERSON> was toppled by a military coup. Since Gen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> completed his first term in 1952, no Argentine president has finished the traditional six years in office. A military coup ousted <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in 1955 and the party that carries his name was banned for the next 18 years. `` This is a victory for democracy,'' <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> said in a seven-minute speech taped at Government House and broadcast nationwide at 9 p.m. `` We will complete the triumph of today in the ballot boxes.'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> announced last month that elections would be held in May. No exact date was set until <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s speech. The two main political parties already have begun campaigning. <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>, the presidential candidate of <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s centrist <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, began his campaign on Sept. 30 with a multicity tour. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> started his campaign Saturday night. About 75,000 Peronists gathered Monday in the <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plate </LOCATION> soccer stadium to celebrate the anniversary of <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>'s release from prison in 1945 _ a pivotal event in Argentine history. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> went on to dominate Argentine politics for years. The third main candidate is <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> of the Union of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Both <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> and <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON> are lawyers and provincial governors. <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> is an engineer, former economy minister and ex-ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Up for election are the presidency, vice presidency, many seats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, and thousands of provincial mayors and local legislators. The main issue probably will be the economy. Gross national production has been stagnant for eight years and inflation has soared. The cost of living increased by 440 percent over the past 12 months. Public employees including doctors, railway engineers, teachers and mail carriers hold frequent strikes to press demands that wages keep pace with inflation. Polls indicate that <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, who promises wage increases and tax cuts, has a wide early lead over the more conservative <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>. The surveys gave <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> virtually no chance of victory. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s inauguration on Dec. 10, 1983, following elections that October, ended nearly eight years of right-wing military dictatorships. An attorney and human rights leader, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> has defended his political record by stressing that whatever he did took place in a democracy. `` In stable democracies, this occurrence -LRB- an election -RRB- is routine,'' said <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> on Tuesday, dressed in a dark suit and seated at an ornate desk. `` In our country, which is subject to shocks and disasters, it is a singular accomplishment. `` I have been an actor in a historic episode, but the authors, those ultimately responsible, are each and every Argentine. None should be indifferent to the jubilation ... and true national celebration.''
