<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     10-18 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>`What Did He See?,' A Play by Richard Foreman, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stage is a medieval dungeon with furniture and costumes that could have come from a seedy <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> antique shop. Plexiglas panels separate the actors from the audience, forcing the performers to wear body microphones so they can be heard. One cast member, sporting a black beret festooned with tiny pink roses, resembles a prancing <PERSON> Che </PERSON> <PERSON> Guevara </PERSON> masquerading as <PERSON> Isadora </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>. A second performer dresses in what looks like a nurse's uniform _ only she's wearing patent leather shoes topped with little black bows A third actor wears red pajamas and a red stocking cap. He's the hero of the piece, or at least the performer with the most lines. It's hard to learn anything about these people in `` What Did He See?'' _ <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>'s latest exercise in avant-garde incomprehensibility that opened Tuesday at off-Broadway's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival Public Theater. The three-character play lasts one hour. It seems like more, especially if you attempt to decipher what the author is trying to say. <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> should know, since he wrote, directed and designed the production. It's theatergoers who are left in the dark. In interviews, <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> has described the play as being about the dangers of retirement or the lure of idleness. You'll have to take him at his word. The evening is mostly a series of independent statements. For example, the pajama-clad hero announces, `` I have to tell the truth. I no longer function as a normal human being.'' He's right The actors work hard at seeming to believe all they have to say. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, best known as the villain in the film thriller `` No Way Out,'' projects what appears to be an appropriate air of desperation. <PERSON> Lili </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rocco </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisto </PERSON> are his mysterious sidekicks, the people who alternately support or berate him, depending on the whims of the playwright. Their dedication is admirable. The title of the play asks `` What Did He See?'' It poses a murky question that can only have one answer _ not very much.
</TEXT>
