<HEAD>Marches, Strikes Disrupt Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist-led <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s largest union, launched its `` Day of Action'' Tuesday with marches in all major cities and strikes that disruped public services. The one-day walkout was to support demands for an increase in the minimum monthly wage from $ 758 to $ 968. The confederation also is asking for protection of purchasing power, more employment, better working conditions and retirement protection. Tuesday's strike hit hardest public transportation, the postal service and the state-run electricity company. But it is only a foretaste of more widespread strikes scheduled for Thursday by the other unions representing public employees. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Durafour </PERSON>, the civil service minister, has refused to consider any new pay increases for 1988. Talks between the government and the unions on 1989 salaries are to begin soon. Also joining the strike were employees at French diplomatic posts around the world, where staff are fighting a series of cuts in their cost-of-living allowments. It coincided with a nationwide strike by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s nurses and hospital employees who demand higher wages. The nurses want $ 325 a month more. The government has offered about $ 105, depending on experience and seniority. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, on a visit to <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION>, told a group of nurses that they were asking `` much too much,'' saying the government of Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> already had `` given a lot.'' The workers' demonstration in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> turned out 100,000 people, according to the union. Police estimated the crowd at 15,000 to 20,000. About 5,000 marched in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bordeaux </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Marseille </LOCATION>, each and smaller demonstrations were held in other cities. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> subway ran at about 50 percent to 70 percent of its normal service Tuesday, while service was normal in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Marseille </LOCATION>. Long distrance rail lines were practically normal in most parts of the country, except for the west, where a third of the scheduled trains did not run. Hardest hit was the state-run electric company. Sporadic power cuts hit nearly all areas. The postal service also was heavily affected. Strikes in main sorting centers spelled delays of mail for the next several days.
