<HEAD>Hirohito's Condition Grows Worse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The condition of 87-year-old Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> apparently grew worse early Wednesday after he vomited blood in a health crisis that began a month ago. Palace spokesman <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said, however, that the emperor was resting and there was no need for concern, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. The palace said <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> coughed up a small amount of blood around midnight Tuesday, followed by a discharge of blood from his bowels, and that doctors administered .42 pints in blood transfusions. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has discharged blood intermittently since Sept. 19, when an intestinal hemorrhage caused him to vomit a substantial amount of blood and confined him to intensive care. In one month he has received 20.2 pints in transfusions, according to news reports. Persistent news media reports have said <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has cancer in the area of his upper intestine. The palace has refused to comment and asked news organizations to refrain from speculation that could dishearten the emperor. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s pulse was rising slowly and reached 101 by Wednesday morning, up from 94 a day earlier. He ran a slight fever of 99.1 degrees, <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> told a regular news briefing. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s normal temperature is about 95.9. Court physicians have unsuccessfully tried to combat his anemia with blood transfusions. In recent days they have allowed the world's oldest living monarch to take a few spoonfuls of weak porridge, and acknowledged he is losing strength because his intravenous feedings can not supply enough nutrients.
