Thursday. <PERSON> Clint </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleishour </PERSON> and his five sons were lifted off their disabled sailboat, <PERSON> Paloma </PERSON>, after eight days without food and five days without water. <PERSON> Fleishour </PERSON> said Tuesday that the crew of the Early Light, whom he knew only as <PERSON> John </PERSON> and `` Stretch,'' gave him and his sons five gallons of water, a fish and some fishing equipment. The two boats planned to sail together, but the Early Light headed in a more westerly direction, he said. `` They were n't in any trouble at all when we saw them,'' Fleishour said. `` They said they had 100 gallons of water and lots of groceries on board. They seemed like they were in really good shape.'' Although the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> released few details about the Early Light, <PERSON> Fleishour </PERSON> said the crew told him they were headed from <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, for <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION>.
