<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv19   10-18 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 19,0602</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Oct 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Extreme Views on the Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A seldom mentioned consequence of the spectacular collapse of securities markets one year ago today is that it seems to have made almost anything sound plausible. What, for example? Well, double digit inflation and interest rates, another market collapse to 500 points on the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average, depression _ or, if you prefer, the most stunningly strong economy you could ever imagine. People out there are peddling all those notions, and others, and many of them are considered investment advisers. No matter how their views might differ they share one belief in common: Fear sells. Consider this advertisement for <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s International Gold Report: `` How to Cash in on the <ORGANIZATION> Dukakis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disaster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Let <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> Make You a Millionaire.'' The thesis is that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his Cabinet member, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, would spend the nation into bankrupcty, leaving gold as the only sane way for people to make money or protect what they already have. What if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wins? `` In either case _ <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar will hit the pits long before the economy goes thud. Bank on it. Inflation will settle in like lice on the body politic,'' the ad says. Adrian Day, publisher of <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>'s Investment Analyst, claims to be `` the man who made more money for more people than any investment adviser in history,'' but that's not the reason he is selling bad times. `` I'm not writing just to tell you what a great guy I am,'' he says, but to warn you `` that the next couple of years will be tougher, meaner and more treacherous than any period in the last two decades.'' On the anniversary of the great stock market crash it is n't only the market letter writers who are offering unusual views. Some large brokerage houses are, in effect and sometimes in words, declaring that we are now in a new era. The new era, it is suggested, calls for investments in sound values rather than in hot stocks, a long-term rather than a short-term view, reasonable expectations, a concern for fundamental values and the like. But a new era? The truth is that such concepts have never gone out of style, except in some areas of the securities community, they being fundamental to investing as opposed to trading. Economists also, but perhaps to a lesser extent, have had their thinking affected by the big collapse. Among some, there appears to have developed a competition to find where the economy's weak spots may be developing. As a result, falling unemployment and rising production repeatedly have been viewed with alarm. More recently, the recession-watchers have shifted to inventory buildups. And almost constantly, retail sales are watched for signs. Perhaps the zaniest fear of all is that expressed by those who view the anniversary of the 1987 crash, by itself, as somehow capable of stirring up another disaster. The economy, meanwhile, has performed as well as it possibly could, given the problems of budget and trade deficits. It has shown much more assurance, steadiness, restraint and sense of direction than have its observers. It suggests, oddly, that the peddlers of fear and the extreme thinkers may be doing some good. Conceivably, their reminders might have something to do with keeping the economy on the straight and narrow.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed Oct 19</NOTE>
