<HEAD>Religious Right Program Falters But Is Now Political Staple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the twilight of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s administration, he has n't pulled off most of his social programs dear to the religious right, but he's made them practically a political staple They simmer in the current national campaign, and religious scholars say <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has excelled at using his office as a `` bully pulpit'' for his upbeat-style sermonizing. `` The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years have been good for public theology'' despite its often thin quality, writes church historian <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marty </PERSON>. `` Religion, which had seemed a private affair in the 1970s, went public again in the l980s.'' <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> notes that in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency, growing attention has centered on such issues as values, virtue, education, moral formation, sexuality, family life, abortion and euthanasia Rabbi <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> writes in the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` is clearly the dominant <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> theologian of the l980s.'' But the content, he adds, is `` only sparkling optimisim _ theological <ORGANIZATION> Perrier </ORGANIZATION>.'' While <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has not achieved most of his social agenda, such as banning abortion, reinstating prayers in schools and providing tax credits for children in private schools, he's still preaching them. They're also backed by his party's candidate to succeed him, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Says <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: `` Although we Americans have done much to put our national life back on the firm foundation of traditional values, there is still a great deal to be done.'' He told a summer Youth for Christ rally in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that `` as a nation we must embrace our faith, for as long as we endeavor to do good ... we will find our strength, our hope and our true happiness in prayer and the Lord's will.'' Although <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> rarely attends church himself, he strikes his vintage religious chords. He told the youths: `` I would like someday to entertain an atheist at dinner and serve the most gourmet, perfect dinner that has ever been served, and then at the end of the meal, ask that atheist if he believes there's a cook.'' He said 4,000 abortions a day `` must stop,'' and he said Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` believes with me'' about it. `` Abortion is the taking of a human life.'' `` So far, we have n't succeeded in persusading the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to enact legislation that would once again permit voluntary prayer in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s schools,'' he said. `` But I'm convinced that, one day soon, such a measure will be passed.'' In <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has repeatedly rejected measures to authorize school prayers, give tax breaks for for private school tuition or to amend the constitution to overturn the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision allowing abortion. Some leaders of the religious right, which had strongly backed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for the presidency, have criticized him as not pushing hard enough for the measures, suggesting he gave them only lip service. While the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> right emerged as a political force in the 1980s, it is losing `` influence on the national level,'' says historian <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribuffo </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. However, historian <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> advices against underestimating it, saying it `` did get people talking about the family and personal values.'' He says it has gained legitimacy by adding `` scores of causes'' to its prime anti-abortion cause, and also has overcome objections to its involvement in politics. `` By and large the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> won its point'' _ that it had a legitimate voice in politics, <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> writes in Context, his journal of commentary on religion and culture. But he says the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> rightists `` did not win much'' in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. `` They wanted less government and they got more; they wanted less debt and ended up with the greatest ever; they wanted dismantled social welfare programs and got some, but it was selective.'' However, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asserted a `` major victory'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s recent upholding of an act allowing grants to religious groups to counsel the young against promiscuity. On that subject, he offered his advice to 9000 youths at their <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Evangelism, saying `` it's important for you not to pay any attention at all to all those who say that promiscuity is somehow stylish or rewarding.'' He said `` the right thing to do is to wait for that one special person.'' To be true in marriage, he said, `` you can start being true to that one special person beginning now.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also took credit for the Equal Rights Act, giving religious groups the same right to meet after school the same as other clubs. However, schools are still refusing to do so, challenging the law in court. Recalling a story of the country's origins, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> played one of his frequent themes: `` If <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> rose to invoke the Almighty as the Constitution itself was being drafted _ if the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> opens each day with prayer _ then is n't it time we let God back into the classroom?''
</TEXT>
