<HEAD>Television Serves as Islamic Moral Guardian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Viewers may tire of a mullah chanting from the Moslem holy book, but there is no alternative when he's on The government runs television in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and uses it as a watchdog of Islamic morality. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> television has prepared interesting programs reflecting Islamic social values for the October-to-December quarter,'' program director <PERSON> Zaheer </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> told the government news agency. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, he said that should not be interpreted as fundamentalist or reactionary. <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> dismissed the self-righteous view of Western television as a sinkhole of promiscuity, alcoholism and drug addiction, but also said there are basic differences between East and West, Moslem and non-Moslem. `` We want to make -LRB- the young -RRB- aware of the positive values in our society,'' he said. `` We do n't see the past of any society as a separate entity. It is a progression and we say we are a progressive religion.'' Television is a tool for preserving Pakistani culture, <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> said, and mentioned such things as keeping traditional dress from being supplanted by T-shirts, jeans and three-piece suits. Weekly television series display the cultures of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s five provinces. Love is a common theme, with the young in search of love often pitted against an older generation clinging to the tradition of arranged marriages. `` We do n't believe in sermonizing through the box,'' <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> said. `` We do not talk down to people; we talk to people.'' A series called `` Waris'' was a favorite of the late President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>. It was set in the interior of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> province and told of a powerful, dictatorial landowner who clashed with his sons and tenants. Some Pakistanis said the landlord was intended as a portrayal of former Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, who was hanged in 1979, two years after Gen. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> overthrew him in a mlitary coup. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s daughter <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> now leads the <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which was founded by her father and is the main political opposition. About two months before his death in a plane crash Aug. 17, <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> announced that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> would adopt Islamic law. Women protested in the streets, feeling their hard-won gains would slip away, and whether to implement Islamic law now will be left to the government organized after elections Nov. 16. Subtle changes began occuring on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> television after <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s pronouncement and continued after his death Fewer women were seen on the tube, particularly in commercials, and more covered their heads. Women anchoring the evening news wore headscarves. <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> acknowledged the number of women in commercials has been reduced. Glamorous women in skin-tight dresses slipping into the latest car never were part of Pakistani television, but <PERSON> Bhatti </PERSON> said even tamer depictions of women to sell products is being reduced. If a product is for use by either men or women, a man will appear in the ommercial, he said, and `` the unnecessary use of females to sell products'' will be stopped. Foreign programs will continue to appear because <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s television industry can not produce enough programs to fill the time, but officials are selective, he said Dramas are included, but the emphasis is on such educational and informative programs as documentaries by <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Cousteau </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 24</NOTE>
