<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf from end ``After ...'' to CORRECT that it was
Crawford's final performance, not final performance of show.</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is there life after `` The Phantom of the Opera'' for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>? Emphatically `` yes'' says the man who conquered Broadway last season, carting off every theater award in sight, including a Tony. Now <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> has left the cast of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> production of `` Phantom,'' but even his departure from the hit musical was spectacular. After missing more than a week because of a virus, the star returned Oct. 8 for one final performance. During curtain calls, the entire cast showered <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> with red roses. They were assisted by members of the audience, some of them running down the aisles of the Majestic Theater to toss flowers on the stage. An emotional <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> spoke to the theatergoers, choking on what he said was the same thing he told his mother on his 21st birthday. `` I'd like to thank you for having me,'' he told the cheering crowd. `` You're perfection,'' yelled one enthusiastic woman. But <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> has not hung up his `` Phantom'' mask and put away his makeup for good. The actor plans to do at least a nine-month engagement, beginning next May, in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> company of `` Phantom.'' It's the best possible audition for the movies. `` The film people are there, and they'd see it,'' he says. `` I have got very strong interest and offers from two studios. If I'm in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, I can work on development as it is happening. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> has made movies before. Film buffs know him from `` The Knack,'' `` A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum,'' `` Hello, Dolly!'' and `` How I Won the War.'' But this is the first time a movie will be planned around him. What a difference a hit musical can make to a career. `` I do n't think I was known over here at all,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. In <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, he was a star. He appeared in several hit British television series and had done three big musicals in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION> _ `` <PERSON> Billy </PERSON>,'' `` Flowers for <PERSON> Algernon </PERSON>'' and `` Barnum.'' The last show, an American musical, had an even longer run in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> than it did in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` It ran so long we had births and deaths in the audience,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. `` People died, and we had a woman give birth once. It was like life aboard a 747 on an around-the-world trip.'' `` Phantom'' _ with the help of exposure on national television shows such as `` West 57th Street'' _ has made his face familiar to fans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` When I first opened in ` Phantom' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> even the stage managers would ask, ` Are you <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>?,''' he says. Before he left the show, there were crowds of 50 to 60 people waiting each night at the stage door to see him. And the letters never stopped coming. Every day he would receive more than 100 letters, some from overseas and addressed simply, `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, Broadway, <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>'s most dedicated followers have been an informal group of Britishers called the OGRES, which stands for Opera Ghosts Return Enthusiasts. Many of them came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for his final Broadway appearance. Some had been here twice before, unfurling banners down the Majestic alleyway that proclaimed `` Bring Him Home.'' `` There are about 25 of them and they wo n't let anyone else join,'' he says. `` They are very exclusive. And if anyone misbehaves, they are out. Or if they bother me. They do n't like to annoy me. They are very good to me.'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> also has widened his appeal with his first solo recording, `` Songs From the Stage and Screen'' that he made before he opened `` Phantom'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` They have sold over 200,000 copies on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, so it's on its way to gold,'' he says `` And I'm very pleased. There was a terrific amount of care gone into that record.'' The album, which includes a medley of songs from `` West Side Story'' and such Broadway classics as `` If I Loved You,'' `` Memory'' and `` You'll Never Walk Alone,'' has sold well all over the world. `` It's triple platinum in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, which means it has sold 20,000 copies,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> says. `` Even the sheep are buying it.'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> will go back into the recording studio early next year in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to record a second album, this time a collection of love songs. He hopes to include `` Music of the Night,'' his big number from `` Phantom,'' if composer <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> grants his permission. The performer also is considering several new Broadway musicals, although none he can talk about. `` But it's nice that I've been asked,'' he says. `` And one of them is of particular interest to me.'' After his final performance in `` Phantom,'' a role now being played by <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> to make a documentary film for a British charity. Then he may begin to relax for a few weeks. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> admits he'll miss the hoopla that accompanied his 10-month `` Phantom'' run in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, although there are tradeoffs. `` I'll be glad to have it quiet after all that attention,'' he says. `` You need that quiet whenever you have finished a show that is an event.''
</TEXT>
