<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pardon for Butting In But USDA Has Something To Say About Goats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In case <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> want to talk about goats, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has some new material speechwriters can use. No kidding. It would be good for rebuttal, too. Goats are among the most non-controversial farm topics around. They have n't been involved in any huge <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> subsidy flap and are not a big legislative issue on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. Moreover, while city folk may have trouble identifying with modern feedlots that send beef to their tables, or the farrowing pens that turn out pork chops and sausage, just about everyone feels good about goats. `` Since before biblical times, goats may have been the most useful of domesticated animal, producing milk for drinking or for cheese, gourmet meat -LRB- cabrito -RRB-, leather, and fiber for clothing -LRB- cashmere or Angora -RRB-, not to be confused with Angora -LRB- rabbit -RRB- wool,'' says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The goat report is the latest in a series of single-sheet papers turned out by the agency's Office for Small-Scale Agriculture. Others include such topics as sheep, mushrooms, foliage plants, herbs, wildflowers and specialty vegetables. Goats are relatively clean and make `` fine pets and show animals,'' the report said. Worldwide, there may be as many 460 million, which produce an estimated 4.5 million metric tons of milk annually. But before people quit the city job, politics or other endeavor, there are some things they should know about raising goats for a living or as a supplement to other income. `` They, of course, need care to keep dogs away and skillful management to prevent diseases and internal as well as external parasites such as lice, mites and fleas,'' the report said. `` Goat milk is so respected that there have been people who began raising dairy goats before learning whether they could sell the milk or knew how to make cheese.'' One problem is that in at least 21 states, goat milk must be pasteurized, or heated to a prescribed temperature, to kill potentially harmful bacteria. And pasteurization can cost a bundle for equipment. Where milk can be sold raw, herds must be licensed and the nannies must be carefully tested and kept free of brucellosis and tuberculosis, which are contagious to humans. Lest anyone sneer at someone's plan to operate a goat ranch on a couple of acres beyond the zoning of outer surburbia, goats have assumed something of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hauteur of late. In 1987, for the first time, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recognized the merits of the dairy goat, proclaiming a National Dairy Goat Awareness Week. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, it was said, supported the idea enthusiastically and had recalled `` with fondness the time about 25 years ago when each or our two doe goats had quintuplets on our ranch in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.'' Goats are raised for non-dairy purposes such as for meat and leather or fine hair, the report said. Farmers and ranchers who are already pasturing some sheep or cattle, or both, may be able to add some goats without any problems. `` Goats eat some plants that sheep and cattle do n't seek, so they are not mutually exclusive,'' the report said. `` They pasture well together.'' The meat, or cabrito _ sometimes called chevon _ has little fat and `` tastes better than venison,'' the report said. Worldwide, production is more than 1.2 million metric tons a year. `` With a flock of 350 to 400 Spanish does, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckholz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dripping </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, who raises goats for meat, annually sells their offspring for meat at eight months of age for $ 30 a head,'' the report said. `` Since the stock is tough, thrifty and hardy, he has lots of pasture and some Pyrenees dogs to keep predators such as coyotes and wild dogs at bay, <PERSON> Buckholz </PERSON>'s expenses are relatively small.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> and <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, sometimes feed young goats, or kids, only about two months until they reach 35 to 40 pounds. The young animals are then sold at nearly $ 1 a pound in the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area, where there is often a shortage of goats in November and December. For free single copies of the report, `` Goats,'' or any of the others published so far, write to: Office for <ORGANIZATION> Small-Scale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, Office of Grants and Program Systems, Room 342-D, Aerospace Building, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20251-2200. Telephone 202?447-3640.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
