<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices continue to climb, but analysts warn that trading will be volatile while <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members hold a series of meetings in hopes of lowering crude oil production. The November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 29 cents Monday to close at $ 15.21 a 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Subsequent contract months settled about 22 cents a barrel higher. Analysts said the November contract had additional strength because of tight supplies. Refined products traded on the exchange followed a similar pattern, with near-term contracts posting the largest gains. The November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up 1.34 cents to settle at 46.76 cents a gallon, while the November contract for home heating oil rose 0.67 cent to 43.88 cents a gallon. Prices zigzagged Monday before rising amid optimism that the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meetings could end the cartel's overproduction problems. `` People are expecting a lot of volatility in the market for the next few weeks,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market still looks strong, but people are afraid it's overbought and will run out of good news to keep it up.'' Oil prices fell below $ 12.30 two weeks ago because of overproduction by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, then began to climb as meetings to discuss the situation approached. This past weekend, oil ministers of the six-nation <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> met and proposed a production ceiling of 18.5 million to 19 million barrels a day for the 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members. The <ORGANIZATION> GCC </ORGANIZATION> proposal is expected to be presented to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s committees on strategy and pricing, which are meeting Thursday in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> also has a ministerial conference scheduled for Nov. 21. `` It's going to be meeting, meeting, meeting, and that's going to keep the market in an uproar,'' <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON> said.
