<SECOND>PM-Drexel, Bjt,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Says It Will Appeal In Effort Remove Judge From Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will appeal a judge's refusal to quit presiding over the government's massive civil-fraud suit against the firm, raising the prospect of more delays and pretrial theatrics in a case that already has acquired celebrity status in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> federal court. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s angry rejection Monday of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s move to disqualify him was seen outwardly as a setback for the Wall Street giant, some attorneys following the courtroom battle saw it as a plus for the defense, which is trying to portray <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> as a victim of prejudice. `` You ca n't lose,'' said one attorney, who spoke on condition he not be identified. `` This effort has to be for the purpose of creating the picture that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is a fine company mistreated by the courts.'' <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> denied <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> motions to stop him from ruling on its case as well as in other cases involving the firm and <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the imprisoned inside trader who implicated <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and others in alleged wrongdoing when he was exposed nearly two years ago. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, a respected 82-year-old jurist who has been presiding over most Boesky-related litigation for more than a year, deemed the defense strategy to remove him a ludicrous, time-wasting ploy. His opinion seemed to further raise the level of antagonism between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> lawyers and the judge since the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filed its wide-ranging fraud suit against the firm and other defendants last month. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> already has chastised several defense lawyers for their conduct in the case and referred two of them to the chief judge of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> federal court for possible disciplinary sanctions. A raucous hearing last week on defense efforts to disqualify <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> on grounds of possible bias featured emotional exchanges between him and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> attorneys, who are among the most highly paid in the country. That session drew a packed audience, unusual in securities law cases. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> lawyers applauded <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s opinion Monday and expressed eagerness to proceed. Private attorneys suing <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> also welcomed the ruling. Defense attorneys did not return telephone calls for comment. But <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said in a statement: `` Our attorneys had a professional obligation to bring this issue before the court. Since it is their considered view that, based on the facts in the motion, Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s position is incorrect, the matter will be placed before the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> claims <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> has a conflict of interest because his wife, <LOCATION> Moselle </LOCATION>, stands to gain $ 30 million from the sale of her stock in <ORGANIZATION> Palais </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Houston-based concern going private in a transaction that indirectly involves <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> financing. Although Mrs. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s financial interest would make it appear that <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> is biased in <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s favor, defense lawyers had argued they wanted a judge whose impartiality could not possibly be questioned by the public. `` There is no financial or business connection, or other relationship between Mrs. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>,'' the judge wrote. `` There is simply no reasonable basis for doubting the court's impartiality in this case by reason of the <ORGANIZATION> Palais </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> stock sale; no facts, no rational basis, have been supplied. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> wrote that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s motion seemed so far-fetched `` as to be ludicrous and hardly a basis for a judge to step aside.'' Privately, many lawyers have speculated the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> defense wants another judge because of <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s reputation as a tough, no-nonsense securities-law expert tending to side with the government in fraud cases. Legal experts familiar with courtroom strategies to disqualify judges doubted the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> effort to remove <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> would prevail. `` It is fairly common to use a motion to disqualify as sort of a diversion,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sometimes the strategy is serious, when there are reasons to fear the judge. Sometimes the motion is made because you do n't like the judge,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` It generally fails, miserably.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and four key employees of the firm Sept. 7 alleging they secretly plotted with <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> to manipulate stock, profit on inside information about corporate takeovers, cheat clients and engage in other frauds. The defendants have denied the charges.
