<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street was kept in the dark, as the law requires, before <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced its $ 11 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The best evidence that there were no widespread leaks of the surprise takeover bid late Monday is that trading in both stocks was about average and there were no big price changes. The offer was announced after the close of trading. Small amounts of insider trading would not affect volumes or prices, but a rumor that traveled far quickly would have pushed <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>'s stock price toward <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>'s offer of $ 90 a share, and trading would have been heavy. In consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Monday, <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> stock rose 62 -LCB- cents a share to $ 60.12 -LCB-. <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> stock rose $ 1.37 -LCB- a share to $ 100. Trading in <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> was 123,100 shares, less than the daily average volume of 232,900 shares so far this month and 233,548 shares so far this year. Trading in <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> was 691,800 shares, slightly above the daily average of 558,790 shares so far this month and 626,242 shares so far this year.
