<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> executives, saying they wo n't be `` beaten, bought or buried,'' filed a lawsuit to halt a hostile takeover of the Alabama-based grocery chain by A & amp; P. The <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has offered $ 30 a share, or $ 210 million for <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION>, which operates supermarkets in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> The latest offer marks the third time in two years that A & amp; P has bid for the company. In announcing the suit filed Monday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> at Mobile, <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Delchamps </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> called the A & amp; P offer `` cheap.'' The lawsuit accused A & amp; P and others of failing to disclose potential violations of antitrust laws and failure to reveal an alleged plan to financially cripple <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> even if it fails to buy the company. <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> said A & amp; P's motive was to either purchase the firm `` at a cheap price and proceed with its plan to achieve dominance in the Gulf Coast retail stores market'' or cause the firm to suffer high legal bills and induce a leverage buyout that would weaken <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> as a competitor. `` A & amp; P has not been able to compete with us effectively in the marketplace, so it has obviously decided, ` If you ca n't beat them, buy them or bury them with investment bankers and lawyers.' We do n't intend to be beaten, bought or buried,'' <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> said. A & amp; P spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rourke </PERSON> could not be reached for comment Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> operates 102 grocery stores and six liquor stores. A & amp; P, headquartered in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, is 52 percent owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Tengelmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. A & amp; P made its first offer for <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> in October 1986, another in October 1987 and another this month. Between the first and last attempts, the offering price has risen from $ 23 to $ 30 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION>' stock was trading at $ 26.50 a share in the over-the-counter market Monday afternoon, up 50 cents from Friday, while A & amp; P's stock was down 37 -LCB- cents at $ 46.62 -LCB- a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Delchamps </ORGANIZATION> had sales of about $ 700 million last year. A & amp; P had sales of $ 9.6 billion in 1987, from its 1,170 stores in this country and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>.
