<HEAD>Harvard Panel Says National Debt Won't Solve Itself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The next president will have to take major steps to turn around an economy destabilized by an entrenched budget deficit and policy flaws, say economic advisers of varying political stripes in a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> report. In a set of eight papers, experts from consumer activist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> to Nobel laureate <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuelson </PERSON> offer the next president economic advice amid a presidential campaign that the magazine says has produced `` a lot of partisan noisiness'' but little serious deliberation. `` There's a fundamental basic instability in the economic system right now,'' <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> Editor <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said Monday, summing up the papers. The magazine had asked panel members to write memos advising the next president on a range of economic issues. The 42-page report will appear in the magazine's November-December issue. The underlying conclusion: a fundamental instability in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic system needs to be addressed. Indeed, the federal budget deficit is so deeply rooted that it wo n't solve itself in the normal course of economic events. <PERSON> Samuelson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> professor emeritus, argues that fear of alienating voters has `` frightened away all candidates from even discussing vital economic issues.'' The new president, he says, should spend his first year trying to reduce the deficit from about 3 percent of the nation's $ 4 trillion gross national product toward 2 percent, and, ultimately, by 1992 eliminating all deficit that is n't cyclical. A basic structural deficit is one that exists regardless of prevailing economic conditions, so that public debt rises even after the nation returns to full employment. Cyclical deficits are tied to inflation, unemployment and other economic conditions. `` When asked how to tame a basic deficit, one might answer prosaically: ` By expenditure cuts and tax increases.''' But <PERSON> Samuelson </PERSON> says the new president needs to abandon the notion that the deficit can be reduced by either cutting spending or raising taxes or a 50-50 combination. The experts _ two of whom advise the presidential candidates, Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ offer detailed advice for increasing capital formation, modernizing the nation's manufacturing base and overhauling public education. `` Tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people the truth _ that today's apparent prosperity is being borrowed from the future, that our children will be angry and frustrated when they are left with a lower standard of living,'' advises <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prestowitz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former counselor for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> affairs to the Secretary of Commerce. <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, a thorn in the side of big business for 25 years, surprisingly argues that government can learn from business to become more efficient, humane, creative and responsive. `` -LRB- The next president -RRB- should break through the legendary Oval Office cocoon to communicate regularly and directly with federal workers,'' he says. `` He should visit major departments, mix it up with the employees, listen to their ideas, stimulate their thinking and remind them of the importance of their mission.'' Conservative economist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> adviser, counsels avoiding protectionist policies that some industries may press for during the long road back to trade balance. `` If you accede to these pressures, you would not only hurt American consumers and weaken the competitiveness of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry, but would also risk the start of a protectionist trade war,'' he writes. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> cites research showing that if current demographic and economic trends continue, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses will have to hire a million new workers a year who ca n't read, write or count _ at an annual cost to industry of $ 25 `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government spends more money on agriculture research than it does on education research. It's no wonder we know more about pork bellies and soybean futures than we do about our schools,'' he said.
</TEXT>
