<HEAD>State To Hike Withholding Rate On Bonuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> says it will place a higher wihholding tax on bonuses, commissions and other supplemental wages to make it harder for those in the financial services industry to evade taxes. The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday that starting Jan. 1, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> will hike its withholding tax to 7.875 percent from 5 percent on supplemental income sources unless taxpayers make prior arrangements to have withholding taxes figured at the same rate as regular wages. State Tax Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetzler </PERSON> said the change stems from a tax department investigation that turned up thousands of tax evaders at prominent Wall Street brokerages and investment houses, including employees at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. When arrests were made of some top-level employees of those businesses in April, former Tax Commissioner <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> said state officials were `` numbed and shocked'' at how widespread the tax cheating had become on Wall Street. At that time, <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> said the state had found more than 5,700 income tax evaders, including 1,519 people with salaries of more than $ 50,000 a year. The probe revealed that many brokers and investment counselors were properly paying state income taxes on their regular salaries. But they were found to be paying the 5 percent withholding tax and no more on the bonuses, partnership distributions and other supplemental income they were receiving. In many cases, said tax department spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickard </PERSON>, non-salary income is far larger than the regular pay the executives get. <PERSON> Rickard </PERSON> said he had no estimate of how much in taxes experts feel the state is getting cheated out of in that manner. According to <PERSON> Wetzler </PERSON>, the changes on bonus and commission withholding is expected to bring the state about $ 55 million more in the fiscal year ending March 31, 1989, and $ 90 million more in the fiscal year beginning the next day. Tax officials said the state has now matched a list of employees of 1,100 banks, investment firms and stock brokerages with a list of people not filing income tax returns. <PERSON> Rickard </PERSON> said 10,000 warning letters will be mailed by the tax department this week to people the state suspects of not properly filing returns. According to the spokesman, the state is continuing the process of settling accounts with those taxpayers found to be shortchanging the state this spring. He said tax officials are expanding their probe to other fields where some workers earn big bonuses or commissions, such as real estate.
