<HEAD>Exchange Names New Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new governing council of the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday named bank president <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Quo-wei </PERSON> as it chairman. It also announced the appointment of <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuen </PERSON> as the exchange's chief executive to succeed <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fell </PERSON>, who was appointed to the post in the aftermath of last October's market crash. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Hang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seng </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>, was one of five nonbrokers appointed to the 22-member council by the government from outside the exchange's membership. Prior to his appointment, <PERSON> Yuen </PERSON> was managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scrimgeour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vickers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. The appointments completed a shakeup of the exchange's management, transforming the council from a virtual private club of local brokers into a more broadly representative body The chanmges followed criticism of the closure of the market during last October's global crash and a bribery scandal that has resulted in the arrest of eight former exchange officials. Four seats in the new council are reserved for individual members; four for officers of corporate brokerages; five for independent representatives of the public, the investment community and listed companies; and one for the chief executive. The remaining seats are open to any members. Previously, the exchange was run by a 21-member general committee comprised of individual brokers.
