pvs, Wall Street ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors urged stockholders today to reject <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>'s unsolicited $ 5.23 billion bid for the food and restaurant company. The board described the $ 60-a-share offer as inadequate. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said its board instructed management to work with the company's financial and legal advisers to consider alternative courses that would boost the price of the company's stock and protect the best interests of the company and its shareholders. The company's stock was unchanged at $ 58.62 -LCB- a share in midday trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, a spokesman for Grand Met, said the British conglomerate had no immediate response to today's action by <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> board. In a letter sent to all <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> shareholders, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` The board believes that shareholders would realize greater value by retaining their stake in <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` Now is not an appropriate time to sell the company. Remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the long term to accepting the Grand Met offer,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> added. At a news conference today, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s options could include selling the company to a third party, restructuring <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s finances by selling some businesses or going ahead with a leveraged buyout. He said <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> will give shareholders a better idea of the company's strategy before the deadline for tendering stock to Grand Met expires. `` The offer made by Grand Met, $ 60 a share, is not adequate,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` Greater values are available to the shareholder in the long term.'' Asked what he thought <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s chances were in defending against a takeover bid by a well-heeled suitor, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, `` It ai n't over'til it's over.'' Wall Street analysts had speculated Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> would reject Grand Metropolitan's offer, which was made Oct. 4, and possibly announce a dividend-yielding restructuring in an effort to remain independent or possibly attract a better offer from Grand Metropolitan. There also was speculation that a European `` white knight,'' possibly <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, might emerge as a friendly merger partner. But <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> was not currently up for sale and that `` remaining independent would be a superior alternative over the long term to accepting the Grand Met offer.'' In his letter to shareholders, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, `` The board found that Grand Met's offer failed to reflect the values currently being developed at <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> and its subsidiaries under programs that are in the process of being implemented.'' Those programs include `` reinvesting'' in the company's core businesses, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified international food company with operations in packaged consumer foods, including <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Haagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dazs </ORGANIZATION> products, and restaurants. Among its restuarants are Burger King, Steak and Ale and <PERSON> Bennigan </PERSON>'s. The Grand Met bid is one of two takeover attempts in among giants in the food industry that are currently under way. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 11 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> that would make it the world's largest maker of consumer goods. Like <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> indicated it might fight the takeover.
