<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Health Maintenance Group Mergers Microcosm Of National Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This Midwestern city, once recognized nationally for the swift emergence of health maintenance organizations, is now at the center of an industrywide shakeout. The merger of four <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> health care plans within a few months represents a growing national trend of consolidation among HMOs. `` It sounds like a western, but this town's not big enough for more plans,'' said Dr. C.B. Rebsamen of PruCare of <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, one of three surviving health maintenance plans left in a city that once offered more than 20. `` I think what's happening in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> is an example of what the rest of the country is experiencing,'' said <PERSON> Rebsamen </PERSON>, who is head of the doctor group for PruCare. `` We seem to be experiencing the end of the boost in the industry.'' HMOs, which emerged earlier this decade as an alternative to traditional health insurance, are prepaid plans of health services that include preventive treatment. The plans, buoyed by federal legislation requiring many employers to provide HMOs as an option to employees, offer health services through physician groups controlled by HMO units, independent groups or private physicians who agree to participate. Industry observers say the large number of insolvencies and repeated annual losses for HMOs are due to the rapid expansion in the industry, rising benefit costs, undercapitalization, mismanagement and tough competition. `` What they're suffering most from is shortsightedness and stupidity,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Boland </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Boland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Healthcare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consultants </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a national consulting firm for managed health plans. As much as two-thirds of all HMOs nationally reported losses in 1987, more than any other previous year, <PERSON> Boland </PERSON> said. HMOs have faced the added pressure of the evolution of preferred provider organizations, or PPOs, another three-letter plan that in many cases offers customers more flexibility, choice and accessibility than the traditional HMO, <ORGANIZATION> Boland </ORGANIZATION> said. The combined effect of financial instability and viable competition in the market made initial early growth for HMOs a short-lived phenomenon, he said. `` It really flew in the face of dynamics that are coming back to haunt them,'' <PERSON> Boland </PERSON> said. BlueLincs HMO in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> group, acquired HMO of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, Health Accord of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Healthcare </ORGANIZATION> Plan _ all within four months. `` A unification of four HMOs in less than 120 days is unprecedented in this industry,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowser </PERSON>, executive vice president of BlueLincs, when announcing the last acquisition this past summer. The <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> mergers were not included in the most recent national quarterly report issued by <ORGANIZATION> InterStudy </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit research group based in <LOCATION> Excelsior </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, that studies the health maintenance industry. But the activity has not gone unnoticed, said senior <ORGANIZATION> InterStudy </ORGANIZATION> researcher <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>. `` There's certainly a trend toward consolidation nationally,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. You're either going to have to grow or you're going to have to go with a larger plan.'' In 1985, <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> began to be recognized by health care experts as an example of the growth and expansion of HMOs across the country. In that year, 11 plans were offered in the city of 380,000. `` Few medical markets outside <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> are as highly competitive, and it's doubtful any became so as fast,'' wrote <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>, senior associate editor of <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, in the May 1985 issue of the national health industry magazine. In 1985, there were 480 HMO plans nationwide with 21 million members. The number of plans and participants had grown steadily since 1981, with the largest increase in plans and enrollment in 1985. `` We set up a situation where it was pretty easy to get into the HMO business,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. `` But it's not very easy to stay in. It's a tough business.'' `` HMOs that succeed will have excellent management, will be diversified, and may or may not be legally constituted as HMOs,'' she states in a report on the future of the industry. With the termination of Physicians Health Plan of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, only three plans remain in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, serving nearly 90,000 clients. Nationally, 15 health plans -LRB- not including those merged in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> -RRB- were terminated, merged or acquired by another group in the first quarter of 1988, according to <ORGANIZATION> InterStudy </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said national studies indicate a decrease in growth in the HMO industry with fewer new plans started and a drop in enrollment growth. Last year was the first year since 1981 that enrollment did not increase from the previous year, and the first quarter of 1988 shows a decrease in the number of plans, according to <ORGANIZATION> InterStudy </ORGANIZATION>'s statistics. As of March, there were 648 HMOs in the country serving 31 million members, an increase of 1.7 million clients since the previous quarter, Ms. <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. The growth seemed to peak in June 1987 with 662 plans serving just under 29 million members, she said. `` There's no question that the growth rate is slowing. But it's hardly a dying industry when you see 1.7 million new members,'' she said `` What we see now is the number of new plans is balanced with the number of merged plans.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 22-23</NOTE>
