 <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> says it plans to drill an exploratory oil and gas well this winter from an ice island in the <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> Construction of the island and an ice road connecting it to shore is expected to begin in mid-December, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> permit application said. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s exploration manager, said Monday that drilling of the Karluk prospect would be finished by May 1 to allow removal of all equipment before breakup. The prospect is about eight miles east of the <LOCATION> Endicott </LOCATION> oil field operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. It is inside the barrier islands, on a state lease <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> acquired in 1979 in the joint state-federal <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> lease sale. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> has been interested in the area for quite awhile, <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. He said the company drilled a well on <PERSON> Jeanette </PERSON> <PERSON> Island </PERSON>, about four mile north of the new prospect, several years ago. The well will be <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s first since 1986, when it teamed with Standard on the only well drilled to date in the coastal plain of the nearby <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said there is no particular reason the company has planned the well for this winter, other than that it is a prospect <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> identified some time ago. State oil and gas officials said the 10-year lease on the prospect is about to expire and speculated that might be <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s primary reason for drilling this year The company is planning an ice island that is about 1,000 feet in diameter and about 50 feet thick.
