<HEAD>Past Nobel Winners in Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are past winners of the Nobel Prize in Economics and their accomplishments. The prize was first awarded in 1969. 1969: <PERSON> Ragnar </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON>, Norwegian, and <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON>, Dutch, for development of econometrics. 1970: <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuelson </PERSON>, American, for application of a new scientific analysis to economic theories. 1971: <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuznets </PERSON>, American, for introduction of the concept of the Gross National Product. 1972: <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrow </PERSON>, American, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, British, for contributions to equilibrium and welfare theories. 1973: <PERSON> Wassily </PERSON> <PERSON> Leontief </PERSON>, American, for analysis showing how changes in one economic variable affect other sectors. 1974: <PERSON> Gunnar </PERSON> <PERSON> Myrdal </PERSON>, Swedish, and <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayek </PERSON>, Austrian, for contributions in the theory of money and economic fluctuations. 1975: <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kantorovich </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Tjallig </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koopmans </PERSON>, American, for applying statistical methods to resource allocation. 1976: <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, American, for his development of monetary theory. 1977: <PERSON> Bertil </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohlin </PERSON>, Swedish, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Meade </PERSON>, British, for contributions to the theory of international trade. 1978: <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, American, for pioneering work into the decision - making processes in complex economic organizations 1979: <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, American, and Sir <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, British, for work in economic development research with special regard to the problems of developing countries. 1980: <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, American, pioneering econometric models to forecast economic trends. 1981: <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobin </PERSON>, American, analysis of financial markets and their relations to spending decision, s employment, production and prices. 1982: <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stigler </PERSON>, American, for pioneering studies of industrial production. 1983: <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Debreu </PERSON>, American, for research on equilibrium in a market economy. 1984: Sir <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, British, for developing accounting systems that help governments allocate their financial resources. 1985: <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON>, American, for analysis of savings and financial markets. 1986: <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McGill </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, American, for his contributions to the theory of economic and political decision-making. 1987: <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solow </PERSON>, American, for his contributions to the theory of economic growth. 1988: <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Allais </PERSON>, French, for contributions to the theory of markets and efficient utilization of resources.
