<HEAD>Hercules Introduces New Packaging Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hercules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday introduced a new film-packaging technology that it claimed will double the shelf life of fresh produce. <PERSON> Hercules </PERSON> said its new `` FreshHold'' package system controls the atmosphere inside packages, thereby keeping produce fresh longer and preserving its appearance, taste and color. Hercules, a chemical and aerospace company based in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, said it took five years to develop the packaging. `` The key element is a breathable film that allows fresh produce to continue breathing after packing,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Hercules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineered </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polymers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference. `` This breathable film regulates the rate at which oxygen and carbon dioxide enter and leave the package.'' An initial venture involving broccoli has been successful, <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said. FreshHold packaging has been test-marketed at supermarkets in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. Cauliflower, strawberries, celery, carrots, lettuce and pineapple will be available with the new packaging next year, the company said. While packaged produce now makes up only 3 percent of the billion-dollar <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> produce market, many companies are working on similar concepts to extend shelf life, experts say. The new product also will reduce the amount of ice needed to transport produce across the country. The FreshHold packaging also has some drawbacks, according to experts. The lunglike membrane on top of the film has to be custom designed to the respiration rate of each type of produce held in the box, and it requires good refrigeration for optimum performance. In addition, consumers must be convinced that pre-cut fruits and vegetables are as fresh as those they can choose themselves from the produce bin, the experts say. The produce packaged in FreshHold sells for slightly more than unpackaged fruits and vegetables.
</TEXT>
