<HEAD>Steel Output Of Major Producers Up 8.7 Percent In September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The output of crude steel by producers in the non-Communist world rose 8.7 percent in September to 39.549 million metric tons from 36.384 million tons a year earlier, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> registered the sharpest increase with output rising 12.7 percent to 11.672 million tons in September from 10.36 million tons in the year-earlier month. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s production rose in the same time period by 7.8 percent to 8.638 million tons from 8.01 million tons while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production climbed 7.4 percent to 7.5 million tons from 6.98 million tons. For the first nine months of 1988, the output of crude steel by the non-Communist nations rose 10.6 percent to 351.368 million tons from 317.59 million tons in the year-earlier period. Steel producers in the institute's monthly survey come from 32 countries and account for 59 percent of 1987 world production and for 97 percent of world output excluding the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other countries in the Council for <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> as well as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
