<HEAD>Tactical Battle Heats Up In Fight Over Unix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of companies allied with <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> raised the stakes Tuesday in a battle with other computer giants over control of Unix, a base layer of software that makes it easier for different brands of computers to work together. By banding together, the big computer makers gained more bargaining power in the contest with the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a group that includes <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Unix is portrayed by enthusiasts as a great hope of the computer industry because it would allow programs to run on a wide variety of computers without expensive alteration However, the struggle over Unix has soured computer buyers, who fear the standard is being split in two. Programs written to work with one version of Unix might not run on computers that use another version. Both sides in the contest say they want to unify Unix, but the <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> group </ORGANIZATION> insists that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's Unix System V Release 4.0 should serve as the basis, while the Open Software Foundation says <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s version, <LOCATION> AIX </LOCATION>, should be the core The <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> alliance </ORGANIZATION> scored a small victory when the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> indicated Tuesday that there might be room for compromise. Until now it has made its insistence on <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s AIX a non-negotiable point. `` Nothing has changed on that right now,'' <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> said. `` But that does n't mean the world ca n't change tomorrow. Please bear with us.'' A meeting between AT & amp; T and the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> was scheduled for later in the week, probably Friday, <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> said. The new group rallying around <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's version of Unix is made up of 18 companies, including giants such as <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s Ing. <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olivetti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. SpA The Open Software Foundation was created earlier this year because of concerns that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T was manipulating Unix so it would be best suited to run on its own computers and those of its fast-growing <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> partner, <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But supporters of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's version of Unix, known as System V Release 4.0, say <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has taken steps to ensure that other companies and customers have a big say in the development of Unix. `` What <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T has done is resolve those issues,'' <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindelow </PERSON>, senior vice president for marketing and services at <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview. Among the other companies that have joined the new group are <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gould </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s Ing. <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olivetti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. SpA, <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> and two smaller companies are members of both `` We do n't play favorites,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tei