<HEAD>Citicorp, Wells Fargo Report Earnings Decline, Hanover Posts Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported sharp declines in their third-quarter profits while another large banking concern, <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, posted significantly higher earnings during the same period. But all three companies were ahead for the first three quarters of the year following losses a year ago, when they added to their loan-loss provisions to cover troubled Third World debt. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding company, said that net income for the three months ended Sept. 30 totaled $ 394 million, or $ 1.13 per share, down 25 percent from earnings of $ 528 million, or $ 1.78 a share, in 1987. For the first nine months, the company's profit totaled $ 1.11 billion, or $ 3.17 a share, vs. a $ 1.8 billion loss a year ago. No. 7-ranked Manufacturers Hanover said it earned $ 197.7 million, or $ 3.77 a share, in the third quarter. That was 53 percent higher than net income of $ 129.1 million, or $ 2.73 a share, in 1987. Hanover's nine-month earnings totaled $ 741.2 million, or $ 14.28 a share, compared with a $ 1.1 billion loss last year. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON>, ranked 10th, reported quarterly income of $ 131.7 million, or $ 2.36 per share, down 15 percent from earnings of $ 155 million, or $ 2.77 per share, in the year-ago period. Net income for the first nine months of was $ 376.6 million, or $ 6.75 per share, vs. a loss of $ 60.4 million last year. <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> said its third-quarter results included an after-tax reduction in earnings of $ 22 million as a result of its decision to reclassify $ 566 million of its $ 1.4 billion in loans to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, reflecting the non-payment of interest for 90 or more days on those loans. Last year <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> increased its loan-loss provision by $ 3 billion to $ 4.1 billion. Its loan loss provision so far this year is about 78 percent lower. <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION> said its third-quarter profit included an after-tax gain of $ 98 million from the sale of a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> office building. Helping boost its nine-month profit were net gains of about $ 188 million from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, two branch buildings and <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. The nine-month profit had been hurt a year ago by the company's decision to increase its reserve for possible credit losses by $ 1.7 billion <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> <PERSON> Fargo </PERSON> said market conditions in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where it is based, were favorable, but the reduction in quarterly earnings reflected a $ 369.3 million charge for reducing its portfolio of loans to less developed countries.
