<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market finished higher today in moderate trading, rallying briskly after seesawing gently through much of the trading session. Most of the action centered around the issues of several big food companies that are involved in takeover activity. `` The rest of the market is still on hold,'' said <PERSON> Hildegarde </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Market watchers said the subdued tone was largely due to underlying uneasiness in advance of Wednesday's one-year anniversary of the October stock market collapse On the eve of the anniversary of the debacle, it was another fairly slow day on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, and brokers said they had lots of time on their hands. <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> stock shot up in heavy trading, in response to the $ 90 a share offered late Monday by <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> in an $ 11 billion takeover offer. <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> stock dropped, apparently because investors felt the acquisition would dilute the earnings of the cigarette and food giant. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said it has filed suit against <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> and some of its directors in an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> court. In another major development in the food industry, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said its board of directors unanimously rejected a $ 60-a-share tender offer from Grand Metropolitan of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> later disclosed that it had filed a suit against Grand Met and <ORGANIZATION> Wendell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGAN