<SECOND>AM-Crash-Anniversary, Bjt,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Board Market Makers Less Busy, But Say Their System Still Best</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year ago Wednesday, the world seemed to be collapsing around <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> as he battled and screamed to keep order in three tumbling stocks. `` It was a very scary time,'' said <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, a market maker on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where prices collapsed in frenzied selling on Oct. 19, 1987, put some of his colleagues out of business and severely stretched the limits of others. `` There was disbelief and certainly fear.'' He spent that night in a nearby hotel, rather than returning to his suburban <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> home, wife and teen-age daughter. What really worried him, he said, was what would happen on Oct. 20. `` Logic said it was n't going to happen again,'' he said. `` Emotion said it was.'' In an interview on the eve of the anniversary of the worst stock panic of modern times, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said the anxiety level has fallen sharply, but so has interest in stocks. Like other <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> market makers, known as `` specialists,'' <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> is now more concerned with the absence of buyers and sellers, his bread and butter. `` Ours is a business of feast or famine. Always has been, always will be,'' the 47-year-old said in his native <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> drawl, as he leaned against his trading post on the cavernous <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor in lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s jungle of skyscrapers. `` It's certainly closer to famine now.'' A partner in the specialist firm <ORGANIZATION> Benjamin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jacobson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> has been in the business for more than a decade. During a typical day, he buys and sells thousands of shares in <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tandem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, known on Wall Street as <ORGANIZATION> Sallie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>. As a specialist, his firm has what amounts to a franchise in these and 37 other stocks on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor, acting as an intermediary for buy and sell orders from brokers stationed along the floor perimeters. In return, the specialist firm is obligated to set opening prices and keep trading orderly, largely by selling from its own inventory when other sellers are scarce and buying when buyers are scarce. On Black Monday, Oct. 19, and its volatile aftermath, a marauding avalanche of sellers threatened to overwhelm the ability of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s 54 specialist firms to do their jobs. Many were reluctant to buy stocks because they were uncertain whether other buyers would appear. Others who had spent enormous amounts of borrowed money to buy stocks faced credit crises with their banks. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>'s firm, one of Wall Street's strongest, traded more than $ 1 billion in securities during the week of the crash. The performance of the specialists was criticized in some post-crash studies, which called them a weakness in a system that experienced unprecedented strain. But <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> defended what he called the fairest and most efficient market system, even in the face of new technologies that have replaced many of the trading functions once performed by humans. `` If you ask how the specialists did on Black Monday, you'd get a different answer from every one,'' <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said. `` Some went out of business, some made bad mistakes. But one has to understand what a specialist does. `` We are a pricing mechanism. We're not here to buy every stock for sale,'' he said. `` What we're here to do is make sure it's done in an an orderly fashion. We could have done everything right and the market could still have come down.'' Computers can speed the delivery of buy and sell orders to the trading floor, he said, but the auction process, the bargaining and haggling that inevitably becomes part of securities trading, will always be a human domain. `` You ca n't automate the interface of brokers,'' he contended. `` You ca n't black box that.'' On the day before the anniversary, the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor was relatively quiet, and few people were talking about the crash. `` It's history,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garlinge </PERSON>, an <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> colleague who trades <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock In the first hour, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> traded a few thousand shares of <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> with floor brokers and the price moved up | point _ or 62 -LCB- cents a share to $ 33.50. A blue-coated <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> reporter, who conveys all trades into a computer system that feeds the exchange's electronic ticker tape, dutifully recorded the transactions `` This is slow,'' <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said. The biggest action was a few trading posts away at <ORGANIZATION> Stokes </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoyt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the specialist firm for <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, where brokers were screaming to sell because the stock was up nearly $ 30 a share on a $ 90-a-share takeover offer by <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. Several specialists watching from afar shook their heads in To them, takeovers are bad news because the acquired company's stock will no longer be traded. `` It's a product that we lose,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, another partner in the <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> firm. `` It's very tough to lose a company.''
</TEXT>
