<HEAD>Dollar Holds in Choppy Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished higher against most major currencies Tuesday after a choppy day of trading in the foreign exchange markets. Gold prices fell in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In late trading, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 410.70 a troy ounce, down from $ 411.90 a troy ounce late Monday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency began the day on the upswing in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, buoyed by comments in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> governor <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Larosiere </PERSON> who reiterated support for central bank intervention to achieve exchange rate stability. The dollar then headed lower in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before turning up again in domestic trading. Analysts said that despite the appearance of volatility, the dollar was stuck in the same narrow range it has been trading in since spring, between 1.80 and 1.90 West German marks. `` All we're seeing is the low end of the same range,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It will continue to do that until the election.'' Those following the dollar generally agreed that any drastic moves up or down were unlikely before the presidential election is decided next month. Smaller moves within the established trading range are possible, they said. Indeed, some technical analysts attributed the move upward at the end of day Tuesday to a bounce off the low end of the trading range. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the trading day begins, the dollar rose to 127.70 yen from Monday's 127.20 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it slipped to 127.05 yen. Late in the day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar moved to 127.155, up from 127.065 late Monday. The dollar gained against the pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where it cost $ 1.7515 to buy one pound, cheaper than the $ 1.7530 it cost late Monday. But in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fetched $ 1.74805, up from $ 1.74635 late Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday, were 1.81125 West German marks, up from 1.80875; 1.52925 Swiss francs, up from 1.52745; 1.20075 Canadian dollars, down from 1.20375; 6.1675 French francs, down from 6.1710; and 1,346.50 Italian lire, unchanged. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday, included: 1.8050 West German marks, down from 1.8120; 1.5280 Swiss francs, down from 1.5295; 6.1735 French francs, down from 6.1790; 2.0390 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,345.50 Italian lire, down from 1,348.50, and 1.20095 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2047. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 411.80 a troy ounce, down from $ 412.20 an ounce Monday. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 412.95 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 412.25 an ounce. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell to $ 411.00 an ounce from $ 412.30 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.99 an ounce to close at $ 416.05. On the Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at $ 6.355 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.405 Monday. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LO