<HEAD>Late Rally Lifts Wall Street to Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A late rally catapulted the stock market Tuesday to its highest close since last October's crash, as Wall Street overcame its jitters on the eve of the debacle's one-year anniversary. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 19.38 points to 2,159.85, scoring most of the gain in the waning minutes of the session. The blue-chip average brushed past the previous post-crash high of 2,158.96 reached on Columbus Day, Oct. 10. The crash anniversary `` has probably got some people a little uneasy,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Raftery </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` People should look beyond it; the world is n't coming to an end. Tuesday's post-crash peak was still 21 percent below the all-time high of 2,722.42 reached on Aug. 25, 1987. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8-to-5 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 841 issues up, 568 down and 546 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> totaled 162.5 million shares, up from 119.29 million in Monday's session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 191.79 million shares. Stocks spent most of the session seesawing gently between the plus and minus columns, until the late buying spree. The rally was fueled by takeover activity involving several big food companies, which gave the market support throughout the day. `` There's just rampant takeover speculation going on,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, a partner in the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hummer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATI