<HEAD>Small Businesses Healthy After Crash, Study Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT to Birch, sted Birth; uppicks 5th
graf pvs: The index ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Small business growth has remained healthy after the stock market crash a year ago, with sales and employment gains outpacing those of larger corporations, according to an economic index reported Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its Small Business Growth Index rose sharply in the first half of 1988, to 4.46 from 1.48 for the previous six months. The strongest gains were in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, which recovered quickly from the Oct. 19 stock market plunge, which occured a year ago Wednesday. `` ... The dramatic increase in the Growth Index reflects an overall resiliency within the small business sector,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> who is co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION>. The index measures the semi-annual growth in employment, sales and new incorporations of some 7 million small companies _ defined as those with 100 or fewer employees. The index found that small business employment rose 1.97 percent and sales grew 1.3 percent in the first half of this year, compared with a 1.90 percent jobs gain and 1.06 percent sales rise in the second half of 1987. New incorporations remained steady. While small business sales and employment growth outpaced similar rates for large business, the gap between the two narrowed in the first six months of this year, the report said. In the last half of 1987, small business sales grew at a rate 8.2 times those of large business, but in the first half of 1988, the rate narrowed to 3.7 times, the report said. `` Large business cutbacks, prevalent throughout the 1980s, appear to have bottomed out,'' said <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>. `` Additionally, large business employment is now accelerating and sales growth, almost nonexistent last year, is beginning to rise to the level of high-performing small business.'' The weakest growth area for small business was in the <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> region, where sales dropped 2.35 percent and employment edged up 1.31 percent. This was the only area showing a negative indicator, the report said. The biggest turnaround came in the region that includes <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> where overall sales, employment and new incorporations grew 1.03 percent after a 3.94 drop the previous six months. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> ranked first for employment growth at 2.33 percent, while the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> states led in sales growth with a rise of 2.72 percent, the report said.
