<HEAD>Passengers Apparently Not Shying Away Despite Illness Outbreak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> passengers are not shying away from in-flight meals despite a link between food served aboard some flights and the outbreak of an intestinal illness, an airline spokesman said Tuesday. `` We have n't had any reports of any problems,'' said <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>. `` Can I say that nobody has turned -LRB- airline food -RRB- down? No, I ca n't tell you that. But we have n't heard of anything major.'' Shigellosis has been confirmed in passengers on nine flights from Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> to seven cities: <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> In addition, there was a confirmed case on an in-bound flight from <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON> said Tuesday that possible cases of the illness have been identified by the department on about 145 flights since Sept. 15, including flights overseas to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. State epidemiologist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Osterholm </PERSON> said Monday it's still not clear whether food now being served on <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> flights is safe and <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON> said Tuesday that the situation had not changed. `` I ca n't confirm that it is safe and I ca n't say it is n't,'' <PERSON> Osterholm </PERSON> said. Confirmed cases of the illness have been found among passengers who flew on the airline as late as last Thursday, <PERSON> Osterholm </PERSON> said. All the confirmed cases have been traced to food prepared for the airline at the <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> kitchen, which services <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport That facility serves <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> exclusively and prepares 100,000 meals per week for more than 900 Northwest flights out of the Twin Cities. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlags </PERSON>, a corporate spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday that tests on the company's 360 workers should be complete by Thursday and results should be complete before the weekend is out. She said <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> is testing all in-bound and out-bound food at its kitchen in addition to testing employees. The bacterial infection was first identified in 21 <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vikings </ORGANIZATION> football players and staff in the week after their Oct. 2 game in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. The disease causes intense diarrhea and other symptoms that can last for five to seven days. It spreads easily from person to person. Of people exposed to the bacteria, about 10 percent usually get sick, <PERSON> Osterholm </PERSON> said.
