<HEAD>Burger King President Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After serving two years as president of troubled Burger King, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olcott </PERSON> resigned Tuesday in the fast-food company's second top management shakeup this year. The resignation comes as Burger King's parent, Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is scrambling to defend itself against an unwanted takeover bid. Analysts said it was <PERSON> Olcott </PERSON>'s failure to reverse <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s losing trend that led to his departure Under <PERSON> Olcott </PERSON>, Burger King embarked on an expensive and ultimately disappointing marketing campaign based on the slogan `` We do it like you'd do it.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Maguire </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Olcott </PERSON> `` was n't a marketing man when they needed a marketing man badly.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is in the process of defending itself against an unsolicited $ 5.23 billion tender offer launched by London-based <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts speculated that <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> might opt to sell <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, the world's second-largest hamburger chain, in an effort to preserve its independence. A sale could bring as much as $ 2 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s board unanimously rejected Grand Met's $ 60-a-share offer Tuesday, calling it `` inadequate and not in the best interests of the company and its shareholders.'' `` They're fighting the only battle they can,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The hamburger chain accounts for about one-third of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s sales and about two-thirds of its profits but has not done well recently Its pre-tax profits have decline by more than 50 percent, from $ 119.2 million in fiscal 1986 to $ 48.2 million for the year ended May 31, the company reported. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Tuesday in urging shareholders to reject Grand Met's bid that significant investments have been made to improve Burger King operations. He said improved performance is `` critical'' to the chain. <PERSON> Olcott </PERSON>'s departure marks yet another major management shakeup for the fast-food chain, which has had five chairman and eight presidents since <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> took over in 1967. Most recently, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffery </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> resigned as head of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s ailing restaurant group in June. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president, was named <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s chairman. He had worked previously in mergers and acquisitions at <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, prompting financial analysts to speculate <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> might be preparing to get rid of the Miami-based restaurant chain. `` The guy's good at doing deals,'' <PERSON> McMillin </PERSON> said. `` I've got to think he's been brought in to do a deal.''
